Registers.Name: GePhyId1
Registers.Documentation:
The GE PHY ID 1 address allows 16 bits of the OUI to be observed.

The rationale for mapping the PHY identification into the GE sub-system MDIO map is so that management S/W can identify the device even when the PHY is held in reset.

BitFields.Name: GePhyId1
BitFields.Documentation:
The GE PHY ID 1 address allows 16 bits of the OUI to be observed.

The rationale for mapping the PHY identification into the GE sub-system MDIO map is so that management S/W can identify the device even when the PHY is held in reset.

Registers.Name: GePhyId2
Registers.Documentation: The GE PHY ID 2 address allows 6 bits of the OUI along with the model number and revision number to be observed. The individual fields are broken out in the following rows.

BitFields.Name: GeRevNum
BitFields.Documentation: The GE revision number field allows the device revision number to be observed.

BitFields.Name: GeModelNum
BitFields.Documentation: The GE model number field allows the device model number to be observed.

BitFields.Name: GePhyId2Oui
BitFields.Documentation: The 6 MSBs of the GE PHY ID 2 address allow 6 bits of the OUI to be observed.

Registers.Name: GePkg
Registers.Documentation:
The GE package address allows the device package to be determined. The settings are as follows:

    3'b000  Standard 48-pin package
    3'b001  Standard 64-pin package
    3'b010  Integrated magnetics package
    3'b011  Standard 64-pin package with MDI flip

The model number, revision number and package enable S/W to fully determine the device type.

BitFields.Name: GePkg
BitFields.Documentation:
The GE package address allows the device package to be determined. The settings are as follows:

    3'b000  Standard 48-pin package
    3'b001  Standard 64-pin package
    3'b010  Integrated magnetics package
    3'b011  Standard 64-pin package with MDI flip

The model number, revision number and package enable S/W to fully determine the device type.

Registers.Name: GeBgTmpCoef
Registers.Documentation: The bandgap temperature coefficient register is used to minimize the variation of the bandgap voltage with temperature.

BitFields.Name: GeBgTmpCoef
BitFields.Documentation: The bandgap temperature coefficient register is used to minimize the variation of the bandgap voltage with temperature.

Registers.Name: GeXtalDisInh
Registers.Documentation:
The GE sub-system generates an enable signal for the crystal oscillator. This signal also acts as an active low reset for the 25MHz clock generation circuitry. By default the GE sub-system brings this enable low when one or both of the the power supplies is below the normal operating threshold or when a reset is applied via the reset pin.

By setting this management register the user can prevent the crystal oscillator enable from being deasserted during hardware reset. This significantly reduces the amount of time required before the GE sub-system becomes ready after a hardware reset.

BitFields.Name: GeXtalDisInh
BitFields.Documentation:
The GE sub-system generates an enable signal for the crystal oscillator. This signal also acts as an active low reset for the 25MHz clock generation circuitry. By default the GE sub-system brings this enable low when one or both of the the power supplies is below the normal operating threshold or when a reset is applied via the reset pin.

By setting this management register the user can prevent the crystal oscillator enable from being deasserted during hardware reset. This significantly reduces the amount of time required before the GE sub-system becomes ready after a hardware reset.

Registers.Name: GeRefIs25
Registers.Documentation: The reference clock frequency selection register is intended to support the use of an external 125MHz clock. As this feature is not straight-forward to use it is proposed not to call it out to external customers.

BitFields.Name: GeRefIs25
BitFields.Documentation: The reference clock frequency selection register is intended to support the use of an external 125MHz clock. As this feature is not straight-forward to use it is proposed not to call it out to external customers.

Registers.Name: GeRstClkCtlSv
Registers.Documentation: The reset and clock controller state vector address allows the current state of the associated sequencer to be observed. This is the main sequencer in the GE sub-system.

BitFields.Name: GeRstClkCtlSv
BitFields.Documentation: The reset and clock controller state vector address allows the current state of the associated sequencer to be observed. This is the main sequencer in the GE sub-system.

Registers.Name: GeSftRst
Registers.Documentation:
The soft reset register may be used to reset the GE sub-system.

In the event of a S/W reset the GE sub-system behavior depends on the setting of the GeSftRstCfgEn register. When GeSftRstCfgEn is set the GE sub-system will request a new set of configuration settings from the chip during the S/W reset sequence. When GeSftRstCfgEn is clear the  previously stored configuration settings will simply be reloaded into the corresponding management registers.

BitFields.Name: GeSftRst
BitFields.Documentation:
The soft reset register may be used to reset the GE sub-system.

In the event of a S/W reset the GE sub-system behavior depends on the setting of the GeSftRstCfgEn register. When GeSftRstCfgEn is set the GE sub-system will request a new set of configuration settings from the chip during the S/W reset sequence. When GeSftRstCfgEn is clear the  previously stored configuration settings will simply be reloaded into the corresponding management registers.

Registers.Name: GeSftRstCfgEn
Registers.Documentation: See GeSftRst for details.

BitFields.Name: GeSftRstCfgEn
BitFields.Documentation: See GeSftRst for details.

Registers.Name: GeCfgReq
Registers.Documentation:
The configuration request register allows a managed configuration request to be initiated. This causes the GE sub-system to request a new set of configuration settings from the chip.

Once set this register will remain set until the managed configuration sequence has completed at which point it will be automatically cleared.

Note that whenever a configuration request is handled both the MAC I/F and the PHY are reset so as to ensure that they pick up the new configuration settings.

BitFields.Name: GeCfgReq
BitFields.Documentation:
The configuration request register allows a managed configuration request to be initiated. This causes the GE sub-system to request a new set of configuration settings from the chip.

Once set this register will remain set until the managed configuration sequence has completed at which point it will be automatically cleared.

Note that whenever a configuration request is handled both the MAC I/F and the PHY are reset so as to ensure that they pick up the new configuration settings.

Registers.Name: GeCfgSmpWaitN160nsm1
Registers.Documentation: This register controls the amount of time that the GE sub-system allows for the configuration settings to be prepared before it samples them. It is programmed in units of 160ns. The current default corresponds to 100us.

BitFields.Name: GeCfgSmpWaitN160nsm1
BitFields.Documentation: This register controls the amount of time that the GE sub-system allows for the configuration settings to be prepared before it samples them. It is programmed in units of 160ns. The current default corresponds to 100us.

Registers.Name: GeMacIfRst
Registers.Documentation:
The MAC I/F reset register allows a managed MAC I/F reset sequence to be initiated.

The GE sub-system behavior during the MAC I/F reset sequence depends on the setting of the GeMacIfRstScEn register. When GeMacIfRstScEn is set a reset is applied to the MAC I/F for about 1us after which GeMacIfRst is cleared and normal operation resumes. When GeMacIfRstScEn is clear  a reset is applied to the MAC I/F indefinitely and normal operation only resumes when GeMacIfRst is cleared.

BitFields.Name: GeMacIfRst
BitFields.Documentation:
The MAC I/F reset register allows a managed MAC I/F reset sequence to be initiated.

The GE sub-system behavior during the MAC I/F reset sequence depends on the setting of the GeMacIfRstScEn register. When GeMacIfRstScEn is set a reset is applied to the MAC I/F for about 1us after which GeMacIfRst is cleared and normal operation resumes. When GeMacIfRstScEn is clear  a reset is applied to the MAC I/F indefinitely and normal operation only resumes when GeMacIfRst is cleared.

Registers.Name: GeMacIfRstScEn
Registers.Documentation: See GeMacIfRst for details.

BitFields.Name: GeMacIfRstScEn
BitFields.Documentation: See GeMacIfRst for details.

Registers.Name: GePhyRst
Registers.Documentation:
The PHY reset register allows a managed PHY reset sequence to be initiated.

The GE sub-system behavior during the PHY reset sequence depends on the setting of the GePhyRstScEn register. When GePhyRstScEn is set a reset is applied to the PHY for about 1us after which GePhyRst is cleared and normal operation resumes. When GePhyRstScEn is clear  a reset is applied to the PHY indefinitely and normal operation only resumes when GePhyRst is cleared.

Not that whenever a reset is applied to the PHY a reset is also applied to the MAC I/F.

BitFields.Name: GePhyRst
BitFields.Documentation:
The PHY reset register allows a managed PHY reset sequence to be initiated.

The GE sub-system behavior during the PHY reset sequence depends on the setting of the GePhyRstScEn register. When GePhyRstScEn is set a reset is applied to the PHY for about 1us after which GePhyRst is cleared and normal operation resumes. When GePhyRstScEn is clear  a reset is applied to the PHY indefinitely and normal operation only resumes when GePhyRst is cleared.

Not that whenever a reset is applied to the PHY a reset is also applied to the MAC I/F.

Registers.Name: GePhyRstScEn
Registers.Documentation: See GePhyRst for details.

BitFields.Name: GePhyRstScEn
BitFields.Documentation: See GePhyRst for details.

Registers.Name: GeStat
Registers.Documentation: The GE status address allows various GE sub-system signals to be observed. The individual fields are broken out in the following rows.

BitFields.Name: GeSubsysRdy
BitFields.Documentation: The ge_subsys_rdy signal may be observed here. This signal indicates that the GE sub-system is ready for normal operation.

BitFields.Name: GeCfgReqSig
BitFields.Documentation: The cfg_req signal may be observed here. This signal indicates that the GE sub-system is requesting a new set of configuration settings from the chip.

BitFields.Name: GeMacIfRstSig
BitFields.Documentation: The mac_if_reset signal may be observed here. This is the H/W reset for the MAC I/F.

BitFields.Name: GePhyRstNSig
BitFields.Documentation: The phy_reset_n signal may be observed here. This is the active low H/W reset for the PHY.

BitFields.Name: GeMiMacIfRstDone
BitFields.Documentation: The mi_mac_if_rst_done signal may be observed here. This signal indicates that the requested managed MAC I/F reset sequence has completed.

BitFields.Name: GeMiPhyRstDone
BitFields.Documentation: The mi_phy_rst_done signal may be observed here. This signal indicates that the requested managed PHY reset sequence has completed.

BitFields.Name: GePhyInNrgPd
BitFields.Documentation: The phy_in_nrg_pd signal may be observed here. This signal indicates that the PHY is in the energy detect powerdown mode.

BitFields.Name: GePhyPllLck
BitFields.Documentation: The pll_locked signal may be observed here. This signal indicates that the PHY PLL is locked.

BitFields.Name: GePhyCfgLtchd
BitFields.Documentation: The phy_cfg_is_ltchd signal may be observed here. This signal indicates that the PHY has latched its configuration I/Ps.

Registers.Name: GeIrqEn
Registers.Documentation: The GE interrupt request enable register may be used to control whether or not the interrupt signal is asserted in response to various events. The individual fields are broken out in the following rows.

BitFields.Name: GeMiErrIrqEn
BitFields.Documentation: This bit enables an interrupt in response to an MI framing error.

BitFields.Name: GeResCalErrIrqEn
BitFields.Documentation: This bit enables an interrupt in response to a resistor calibration error.

BitFields.Name: MiIrq
BitFields.Documentation: Setting this bit generates a managed interrupt. This feature is intended to provide a convenient test of the interrupt connectivity.

Registers.Name: GeIrqLat
Registers.Documentation: The GE interrupt request latch address may be used to check which interrupt requests have been triggered since the last time it was read. Each bit will go high when the associated event occurs and will then latch high until it is unlatched by reading. The bits of GeIrqStat go high even when the associated interrupts are not enabled. The individual fields are broken out in the following rows.

BitFields.Name: GeMiErrIrqLh
BitFields.Documentation: This bit indicates that an MI framing error occurred since the last time that GeIrqLat was read.

BitFields.Name: GeResCalErrIrqLh
BitFields.Documentation: This bit indicates that a resistor calibration error occurred since the last time that GeIrqLat was read.

BitFields.Name: MiIrqLh
BitFields.Documentation: This bit indicates that MiIrq was set since the last time that GeIrqLat was read.

Registers.Name: GeClkCfg
Registers.Documentation: This register allows the GE sub-system O/P clock configuration to be controlled. The individual fields are broken out in the following rows.

BitFields.Name: GeClk25En
BitFields.Documentation: The GE sub-system provides a digital 25MHz clock irrespective of whether the reference clock I/P is at 25MHz or 125MHz. Setting GeClk25En causes the GE sub-system to request the chip to drive the digital 25MHz clock at an O/P pin.

BitFields.Name: GeClkHrtFreeEn
BitFields.Documentation: The GE PHY provides a digital free-running heartbeat clock. This clock is sourced either from the reference clock or from the PLL depending on the mode that the PHY is in and on the settings of certain registers. Setting GeClkHrtFreeEn causes the GE sub-system to request the chip to drive the digital  free-running heartbeat clock at an O/P pin.

BitFields.Name: GeClkHrtRcvrEn
BitFields.Documentation: The GE PHY provides a digital recovered heartbeat clock. This clock is sourced either from the reference clock or from the phase selector depending on the mode that the PHY is in and on the settings of certain registers. Setting GeClkHrtFreeEn causes the GE sub-system to request the chip to drive the digital recovered heartbeat clock at an O/P pin.

BitFields.Name: GeRefClkEn
BitFields.Documentation: The differential clock pair from the crystal oscillator is connected to a differential buffer in the GE sub-system. When the buffer is enabled by setting this register a single-ended version of the crystal oscillator clock is driven at the ge_ref_clk O/P pin of the GE sub-system.

BitFields.Name: GeClkFree125En
BitFields.Documentation:
The differential clock pair from the GE PHY PLL is connected to a differential buffer in the GE sub-system. When the buffer is enabled by setting this register a single-ended version of this clock is driven at the ge_clk_free_125 O/P pin of the GE sub-system.

By default the ge_clk_free_125 O/P pin is not driven until the PLL has locked but this can be changed by setting GeClk125NoLckEn.

BitFields.Name: GeClkRcvr125En
BitFields.Documentation:
The differential clock pair from the GE PHY phase selector is connected to a differential buffer in the GE sub-system. When the buffer is enabled by setting this register a single-ended version of this clock is driven at the ge_clk_rcvr_125 O/P pin of the GE sub-system.

By default the ge_clk_rcvr_125 O/P pin is not driven until the PLL has locked but this can be changed by setting GeClk125NoLckEn.

BitFields.Name: GeTclkEn
BitFields.Documentation: The GE PHY provides a differential clock pair for jitter testing. This clock pair is connected to a differential buffer in the GE sub-system. When the buffer is enabled by setting this register a single-ended version of this clock is driven at the ge_tclk O/P pin of the GE sub-system.

Registers.Name: GeMacIfCfg
Registers.Documentation: This register allows the MAC I/F configuration to be controlled. The individual fields are broken out in the following rows.

BitFields.Name: GeRgmiiEn
BitFields.Documentation: This bit allows the choice between RGMII and GMII to be specified.

BitFields.Name: GeRgmiiTxIdEn
BitFields.Documentation: This bit determines whether or not the T/X clock internal delay is enabled.

BitFields.Name: GeRgmiiRxIdEn
BitFields.Documentation: This bit determines whether or not the R/X clock internal delay is enabled.

BitFields.Name: GeRgmiiGtxSel
BitFields.Documentation:
This field allows the RGMII T/X clock delay to be specified in terms of the DLL unit delay (Tu). The settings are as follows:

    3'b000  Delay by   8 x Tu + 400ps
    3'b001  Delay by   6 x Tu + 400ps
    3'b010  Delay by   7 x Tu + 400ps
    3'b110  Delay by   9 x Tu + 400ps
    3'b111  Delay by 10 x Tu + 400ps

Settings not listed are reserved.

The default value for Tu is 200ps and this value may be adjusted using the GeDllTapSel register.

BitFields.Name: GeRgmiiRxSel
BitFields.Documentation: This field allows the RGMII R/X clock delay to be specified. The settings are the same as those for GeRgmiiGtxSel.

Registers.Name: GePhyBaseCfg
Registers.Documentation:
This register allows the PHY base configuration to be controlled. The individual fields are broken out in the following rows.

Note that any register whose label ends with Cfg will not take effect until after the PHY is reset.

BitFields.Name: GeNoPwrCutRst
BitFields.Documentation:
This register allows power to the PHY digital circuitry to be maintained in reset. When this register is set to 1'b1 the PHY digital power supply will not be switched off when the PHY is in reset.

Note that this register has no effect if the PHY digital circuitry is not in its own power island.

BitFields.Name: GeNoPwrCutComa
BitFields.Documentation:
This register allows power to the PHY digital circuitry to be maintained in coma. When this register is set to 1'b1 the PHY digital power supply will not be switched off when the PHY is in the coma mode.

Note that this register has no effect if the PHY digital circuitry is not in its own power island.

BitFields.Name: GeNoPwrCutNrgPd
BitFields.Documentation:
This register allows power to the PHY digital circuitry to be maintained when the cable is unplugged. When this register is set to 1'b1 the PHY digital power supply will not be switched off when the PHY is in the energy detect powerdown mode.

Note this register has no effect if the PHY digital circuitry is not in its own power island.

BitFields.Name: GePhySftPdCfg
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set the PHY will enter S/W powerdown on exit from reset.

BitFields.Name: GeManMdiFlipCfg
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set the order of PHY transceiver lanes is reversed.

BitFields.Name: GeNrgPdEnCfg
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set the PHY will enter energy detect powerdown after a number of seconds of silence on the line.

BitFields.Name: GeNrgPdTxEnCfg
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set the PHY will periodically wake up when in energy detect powerdown and will transmit a number of pulses. This is to avoid a lock-up situation where the PHYs on both ends of the line are in energy detect powerdown.

BitFields.Name: GeB10TeEn
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set the PHY will transmit link pulses and 10BASE-T signals at a lower voltage level in accordance with 10BASE-Te.

BitFields.Name: GeAutoMdiEnCfg
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is clear the PHY will not implement automatic crossover detection.

BitFields.Name: GeManMdixCfg
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set and GeAutoMdiEnCfg is clear the PHY will operate in the MDI-X configuration. In this configuration no crossover is implemented and the logical pairs of the PCS correspond to the physical pairs of the AFE.

Registers.Name: GePhyIfCfg
Registers.Documentation:
This register allows the PHY I/F configuration to be controlled. The individual fields are broken out in the following rows.

Note that any register whose label ends with Cfg will not take effect until after the PHY is reset.

BitFields.Name: GeMiiUseGtxClk
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set the PHY uses the GMII T/X clock when operating in MII mode. This avoids the need for the MAC to have a FIFO on the transmit side.

BitFields.Name: GeRxdInbandEnCfg
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set the PHY will embed in-band signaling on its R/X side.

BitFields.Name: GeFifoDpth
BitFields.Documentation:
This field allows the PHY FIFO depth to be configured. Setting a larger value allows longer (jumbo) packets to be handled but increases latency.

In latency sensitive applications this field should always be left at the default value of 3'b000 as this gives the lowest latency.

Registers.Name: GePhyAdvCfg
Registers.Documentation:
This register allows the PHY advertisement configuration to be controlled. The individual fields are broken out in the following rows.

Note that any register whose label ends with Cfg will not take effect until after the PHY is reset.

BitFields.Name: GeAutonegEnCfg
BitFields.Documentation:
When this bit is clear the PHY will not auto-negotiate. In this case the speed and duplex setting will be forced.

Note that the PHY does not presently support this configuration.

BitFields.Name: GeHd10AdvCfg
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set the PHY will advertise support for 10BASE-T half-duplex.

BitFields.Name: GeFd10AdvCfg
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set the PHY will advertise support for 10BASE-T full-duplex.

BitFields.Name: GeHd100AdvCfg
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set the PHY will advertise support for 100BASE-TX half-duplex.

BitFields.Name: GeFd100AdvCfg
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set the PHY will advertise support for 100BASE-TX full-duplex.

BitFields.Name: GeFd1000AdvCfg
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set the PHY will advertise support for 1000BASE-T full-duplex.

BitFields.Name: GePrefMstrCfg
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set the PHY will advertise a preference to operate as Master when in 1000BASE-T mode.

BitFields.Name: GeDnspTo10EnCfg
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set the PHY is allowed to automatically drop down to 10BASE-T if necessary.

BitFields.Name: GeDnspTo100EnCfg
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set the PHY is allowed to automatically drop down to 100BASE-TX if necessary.

BitFields.Name: GeEee100AdvCfg
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set the PHY will advertise support for 100BASE-TX energy efficient ethernet operation.

BitFields.Name: GeEee1000AdvCfg
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set the PHY will advertise support for 1000BASE-T energy efficient ethernet operation.

Registers.Name: GePhyLedsCfg
Registers.Documentation:
This register allows the PHY LED O/Ps to be configured. The individual fields are broken out in the following rows.

Note that any register whose label ends with Cfg will not take effect until after the PHY is reset.

BitFields.Name: GeLedsFncCfg
BitFields.Documentation: This field allows the behavior of the LED O/Ps to be specified. The default value of 3'b100 specifies that LED A indicates link and blinks on activity, LED B indicates 1000BASE-T operation and LED C indicates 100BASE-TX operation. In the event that different behavior is desired the preferred approach is to change the settings for the individual LED O/Ps. This can be done via the PHY management I/F.

BitFields.Name: GeLedAInvEnCfg
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set the GE sub-system LED A O/P is inverted meaning, for example, that link would be indicated by setting the LED O/P low. Generally it is preferred to operate with this bit set as it means that the chip does not need to supply the power for the external LED but can simply sink current. Powering external LEDs can be problematic as certain colored LEDs have a large forward voltage meaning that they cannot be supplied from 3.3V.

BitFields.Name: GeLedBInvEnCfg
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set the GE sub-system LED B O/P is inverted. See GeLedAInvEnCfg for further details.

BitFields.Name: GeLedCInvEnCfg
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set the GE sub-system LED C O/P is inverted. See GeLedAInvEnCfg for further details.

Registers.Name: GeClk125NoLckEn
Registers.Documentation: By default the 125MHz free-running and recovered clocks are not driven at the O/P pins of the GE sub-system until the PLL has locked. Setting this register allows these clocks to be driven while the PLL is locking.

BitFields.Name: GeClk125NoLckEn
BitFields.Documentation: By default the 125MHz free-running and recovered clocks are not driven at the O/P pins of the GE sub-system until the PLL has locked. Setting this register allows these clocks to be driven while the PLL is locking.

Registers.Name: GeAtestEn
Registers.Documentation: The GE sub-system provides an analog differential I/O pair for making low frequency measurements of internal currents and voltages. These signals may need to be double-bonded so as to share pins with general purpose I/Os. Setting GeAtestEn causes the GE sub-system to request the chip to enable analog test access. The chip is expected to respond to this request by tri-stating any I/Os that share pins with the analog test signals.

BitFields.Name: GeAtestEn
BitFields.Documentation: The GE sub-system provides an analog differential I/O pair for making low frequency measurements of internal currents and voltages. These signals may need to be double-bonded so as to share pins with general purpose I/Os. Setting GeAtestEn causes the GE sub-system to request the chip to enable analog test access. The chip is expected to respond to this request by tri-stating any I/Os that share pins with the analog test signals.

Registers.Name: GeCalReq
Registers.Documentation:
The calibration request register allows a managed calibration request to be initiated. This causes the GE sub-system to calibrate its internal settings with reference to the external precision resistor.

Once set this register will remain set until the managed  calibration sequence has completed at which point it will be automatically cleared.

Note that whenever a  calibration request is handled both the MAC I/F and the PHY are reset so as to ensure that they pick up the new  calibration settings.

BitFields.Name: GeCalReq
BitFields.Documentation:
The calibration request register allows a managed calibration request to be initiated. This causes the GE sub-system to calibrate its internal settings with reference to the external precision resistor.

Once set this register will remain set until the managed  calibration sequence has completed at which point it will be automatically cleared.

Note that whenever a  calibration request is handled both the MAC I/F and the PHY are reset so as to ensure that they pick up the new  calibration settings.

Registers.Name: GeResCalErrIgnEn
Registers.Documentation: When this bit is set the GE sub-system will ignore any resistor calibration errors and will enter its normal mode of operation despite them. Such errors are only expected to occur in the event that an incorrect precision resistor value is used. PHY performance may be degraded in the event of such an error.

BitFields.Name: GeResCalErrIgnEn
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set the GE sub-system will ignore any resistor calibration errors and will enter its normal mode of operation despite them. Such errors are only expected to occur in the event that an incorrect precision resistor value is used. PHY performance may be degraded in the event of such an error.

Registers.Name: GeResCalCntrl
Registers.Documentation: This register allows various GE sub-system resistor calibration control settings to be programmed. The individual fields are broken out in the following rows.

BitFields.Name: GeResCalOffs
BitFields.Documentation: This register allows the resistor calibration setting to be offset. When GeResCalFrcEn is set to 1'b1 this register allows the resistor calibration setting to be forced.

BitFields.Name: GeResCalFrcEn
BitFields.Documentation: This register allows the resistor calibration setting to be forced to the value specified by GeResCalOffs.

Registers.Name: GeRcCalOffs
Registers.Documentation: This register allows the RC calibration setting to be offset.

BitFields.Name: GeRcCalOffs
BitFields.Documentation: This register allows the RC calibration setting to be offset.

Registers.Name: GeCalStat
Registers.Documentation: The GE calibration status address allows various GE calibration status signals to be observed. The individual fields are broken out in the following rows.

BitFields.Name: GeResCalDone
BitFields.Documentation: This bit allows the internal resistor calibration done signal to be observed.

BitFields.Name: GeResCalErr
BitFields.Documentation: This bit allows the internal resistor calibration error signal to be observed.

BitFields.Name: GeResCalData
BitFields.Documentation: This field allows the final resistor calibration setting to be observed.

BitFields.Name: GeRcCalDone
BitFields.Documentation: This bit allows the internal RC calibration done signal to be observed.

BitFields.Name: GeRcCalData
BitFields.Documentation: This field allows the final RC calibration setting to be observed.

Registers.Name: GeMdioCntrl
Registers.Documentation: This register allows various GE sub-system MDIO settings to be programmed. The individual fields are broken out in the following rows.

BitFields.Name: GeMdioGrpAdEn
BitFields.Documentation:
When this bit is set the GE sub-system will respond to any write operation to the group port address which corresponds to address 31. This capability is primarily intended to allow multiple devices to be initialized simultaneously.

Note that the GE PHY core has a separate group address enable register.

BitFields.Name: GeMdioOdInh
BitFields.Documentation: Normally the chip MDIO pin is configured for open drain operation so as to allow several PHY devices to be connected in a system using a single MDIO. In this configuration an external pull-up is required and each PHY device drives its MDIO pin only when it has management data to send and the data value is 1'b0. Setting GeMdioOdInh causes the GE sub-system to request the chip to inhibit open drain operation. The chip is expected to respond by configuring the MDIO pin to drive whenever the device has management data to send irrespective of the data value.

Registers.Name: GeLbCntrl
Registers.Documentation: This register allows various GE sub-system loopback settings to be programmed. The individual fields are broken out in the following rows.

BitFields.Name: GeRxTxLbEn
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set the GE sub-system will implement an internal loopback from its R/X side to its T/X side. This is sometimes referred to as remote loopback or line facing loopback.

BitFields.Name: GeRxTxLbIfInh
BitFields.Documentation: When GeRxTxLbEn is set the default behavior is to loop the R/X data back to the T/X side and at the same time to forward this data to the MAC. However when this bit is set signaling at the I/F is inhibited when performing loopback. This allows the loopback to be performed silently without any data being forwarded to the MAC.

BitFields.Name: GeRxTxExtLbEn
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set the GE sub-system will configure itself to expect an external loopback from the R/X side to the T/X side. This loopback should be implemented at the pins and is intended as a test feature.

Registers.Name: GeDllPd
Registers.Documentation: When this bit is set the GE sub-system DLL is powered down. This feature is intended for evaluation purposes only. In normal operation the MAC I/F controls the DLL powerdown.

BitFields.Name: GeDllPd
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set the GE sub-system DLL is powered down. This feature is intended for evaluation purposes only. In normal operation the MAC I/F controls the DLL powerdown.

Registers.Name: GeDllRst
Registers.Documentation: When this bit is set the GE sub-system DLL is reset. This feature is intended for evaluation purposes only. In normal operation the MAC I/F controls the DLL reset.

BitFields.Name: GeDllRst
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set the GE sub-system DLL is reset. This feature is intended for evaluation purposes only. In normal operation the MAC I/F controls the DLL reset.

Registers.Name: GeDllCntrl
Registers.Documentation: This register provides control of various GE sub-system DLL settings including the regulator voltage. The individual fields are broken out in the following rows.

BitFields.Name: GeDllRegVctl
BitFields.Documentation:
This register allows the DLL regulator voltage to be controlled. The settings are as follows:

    3'b000  Nominal - approximately 0.94V
    3'b001  +1.5%
    3'b010  +3.0%
    3'b011  +4.5%
    3'b100  -6.0%
    3'b101  -4.5%
    3'b110  -3.0%
    3'b111  -1.5%

It is recommended that the MAC I/F be held in reset when changing this setting.

BitFields.Name: GeDllTapSel
BitFields.Documentation:
This register allows the DLL feedback tap point to be selected and this adjusts the DLL unit delay (Tu). The settings are as follows:

    2'b00  Tu = 6.4ns / 32
    2'b01  Tu = 6.4ns / 33
    2'b10  Tu = 6.4ns / 34
 
Settings not listed are reserved.

It is recommended that the MAC I/F be held in reset when changing this setting.

Registers.Name: GeDllTstCntrl
Registers.Documentation: This register allows various GE sub-system DLL test settings to be programmed. The individual fields are broken out in the following rows.

BitFields.Name: GeDllTstClkEn
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set the GE sub-system DLL test clock is enabled and appears at the ge_rgmii_dll_tst_clk O/P. Setting this bit also causes the GE sub-system to request the chip to provide access to this clock. The chip is expected to respond to this request by presenting the DLL test clock at a chip pin.

BitFields.Name: GeDllTstClkSel
BitFields.Documentation:
This register allows the DLL test clock to be specified. The settings are as follows:

    3'b000  Reference clock
    3'b001  Reference clock delayed
    3'b010  T/X clock
    3'b011  T/X clock delayed
    3'b100  R/X clock
    3'b101  R/X clock delayed
    3'b110  Reference clock 1/4 delayed

Settings not listed are reserved.

Registers.Name: GeDllAtstCntrl
Registers.Documentation: This register allows various GE sub-system DLL analog test settings to be programmed. The individual fields are broken out in the following rows.

BitFields.Name: GeDllAtstEn
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set the GE sub-system DLL analog test differential I/O pair is enabled. This allows low frequency measurements of selected currents and voltages within the DLL to be made.

BitFields.Name: GeDllAtstSel
BitFields.Documentation:
This register allows the DLL analog test point to be selected. The settings are as follows:

    2'b00  Regulator voltage
    2'b01  DLL control voltage
    2'b10  Bias current

Settings not listed are reserved.

Registers.Name: GeB10RegenPre
Registers.Documentation: In normal operation the 10BASE-T preamble is consumed while synchronizing 10BASE-T R/X timing and only 1 or 2 bytes of preamble are sent to the MAC. Setting this bit causes the GE sub-system to re-generate a  full 10BASE-T preamble.

BitFields.Name: GeB10RegenPre
BitFields.Documentation: In normal operation the 10BASE-T preamble is consumed while synchronizing 10BASE-T R/X timing and only 1 or 2 bytes of preamble are sent to the MAC. Setting this bit causes the GE sub-system to re-generate a  full 10BASE-T preamble.

Registers.Name: GeNrgPdFrcEn
Registers.Documentation: When this bit is set the PHY is forced into its energy detect powerdown mode and the GE sub-system ge_lped_st O/P indicates the status of the low power energy detect (LPED) circuitry. This feature is intended to allow the LPED circuitry to be conveniently tested.

BitFields.Name: GeNrgPdFrcEn
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set the PHY is forced into its energy detect powerdown mode and the GE sub-system ge_lped_st O/P indicates the status of the low power energy detect (LPED) circuitry. This feature is intended to allow the LPED circuitry to be conveniently tested.

Registers.Name: GeRgmiiIoCntrl
Registers.Documentation: This register allows the characteristics of the RGMII I/O cells to be controlled. The individual fields are broken out in the following rows.

BitFields.Name: GeRgmiiTxHysEn
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set hysteresis is enabled in the RGMII T/X buffers.

BitFields.Name: GeRgmiiRxHysEn
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set hysteresis is enabled in the RGMII R/X buffers.

BitFields.Name: GeRgmiiRxDrv
BitFields.Documentation: This register allows the drive strength of the RGMII R/X buffers to be specified. Lower values correspond to higher drive current.

Registers.Name: GeClkIoCntrl
Registers.Documentation: This register allows the characteristics of the clock I/O cells to be controlled. The individual fields are broken out in the following rows.

BitFields.Name: GeClkHysEn
BitFields.Documentation: When this bit is set hysteresis is enabled in the clock buffers.

BitFields.Name: GeClkDrv
BitFields.Documentation: This register allows the drive strength of the clock buffers to be specified. Lower values correspond to higher drive current.

Registers.Name: GeGenPurCntrl
Registers.Documentation:
The GE general-purpose control register is provided to allow programmability to be added late in a project. Most programmable features are designed in from the start and have dedicated registers. When a need for programmability is recognized late then unassigned bits of the general-purpose control register can be used.

This register is asynchronously reset so that it may be used to provide initial values during power up.

BitFields.Name: GeGenPurCntrl
BitFields.Documentation:
The GE general-purpose control register is provided to allow programmability to be added late in a project. Most programmable features are designed in from the start and have dedicated registers. When a need for programmability is recognized late then unassigned bits of the general-purpose control register can be used.

This register is asynchronously reset so that it may be used to provide initial values during power up.

Registers.Name: GeGenPurStat
Registers.Documentation: The GE general-purpose status address is provided to allow observability to be added late in a project. Most observation points are designed in from the start and have dedicated addresses. When a need for observability is recognized late then unassigned bit mappings of the general-purpose status address can be used.

BitFields.Name: GeGenPurStat
BitFields.Documentation: The GE general-purpose status address is provided to allow observability to be added late in a project. Most observation points are designed in from the start and have dedicated addresses. When a need for observability is recognized late then unassigned bit mappings of the general-purpose status address can be used.

Registers.Name: MiiControl
Registers.Documentation: This address corresponds to the MII control register specified in clause 22.2.4.1 of Std 802.3.

BitFields.Name: UnidirEn
BitFields.Documentation: The unidirectional enable register cannot be written and always reads as 1'b0 since the PHY does not have the ability to transmit data from the MII regardless of whether or not it has determined that a valid link has been established.

BitFields.Name: SpeedSelMsb
BitFields.Documentation:
The speed selection MSB/LSB registers allow the link speed to be manually configured in accordance with the following encoding: 

    2'b00  10 Mb/s
    2'b01  100 Mb/s
    2'b10  1000 Mb/s

The manual configuration setting has no effect unless the AutonegEn register is clear.

These bits are also used by the PHY to report the technology negotiated in the event of an auto-negotiated or parallel detected link. In this case SpeedSelMsb and SpeedSelLsb become valid once AutonegDone is asserted.

BitFields.Name: Coltest
BitFields.Documentation: The collision test register allows the collision test specified in 802.3 clause 22.2.4.1.9 to be enabled.

BitFields.Name: DplxMode
BitFields.Documentation:
The duplex mode register allows the link to be manually configured for full (1'b1) or half duplex (1'b0). The manual configuration setting has no effect unless the AutonegEn register is clear.

This bit is also used by the PHY to report the technology negotiated in the event of an auto-negotiated or parallel detected link. In this case DplxMode becomes valid once AutonegDone is asserted.

BitFields.Name: RestartAneg
BitFields.Documentation:
The restart auto-negotiation register allows the user to initiate renegotiation of the link.

This register is self-clearing.

BitFields.Name: Isolate
BitFields.Documentation: The isolate register allows the PHY to be isolated from the G/MII.

BitFields.Name: SftPd
BitFields.Documentation:
The S/W powerdown register allows the PHY to be placed in S/W powerdown mode. In this mode most of the PHY circuitry is switched off. However MDIO access to all registers is still possible.

The default value for this register is configurable via a pin. This allows the PHY to be held in reset until an appropriate S/W initialization has been performed.

BitFields.Name: AutonegEn
BitFields.Documentation: The auto-negotiation enable register may be cleared in order to force a 10BASE-T or a 100BASE-TX link. The PHY also provides the ability to force a 1000BASE-T link for debug purposes but this capability should not be used in the field as it is non-standard.

BitFields.Name: SpeedSelLsb
BitFields.Documentation: See SpeedSelMsb.

BitFields.Name: Loopback
BitFields.Documentation: The loopback register allows the PHY loopback mode to be engaged. The registers LbMiiSel, LbAllDigSel and LbLdSel determine the type of loopback.

BitFields.Name: SftRst
BitFields.Documentation: The S/W reset register allows a S/W reset cycle to be initiated.

Registers.Name: MiiStatus
Registers.Documentation: This address corresponds to the MII status register specified in clause 22.2.4.2 of Std 802.3.

BitFields.Name: ExtCapable
BitFields.Documentation:
The extended capability bit always reads as 1'b1 indicating that the PHY provides an extended set of capabilities which may be accessed through the extended register set.

The extended register set consists of all of the management registers except 0, 1 and 15.

BitFields.Name: JabberDetLat
BitFields.Documentation: The jabber detect bit indicates that a jabber condition has been detected. Once this bit goes high it latches high until it is unlatched by reading.

BitFields.Name: LinkStatLat
BitFields.Documentation: The link status bit indicates that a valid link has been established. If the link subsequently drops then this bit latches low until it is unlatched by reading.

BitFields.Name: AutonegAble
BitFields.Documentation: The auto-negotiation ability bit always reads as 1'b1 indicating that the PHY has the ability to perform auto-negotiation.

BitFields.Name: RemFltLat
BitFields.Documentation: The remote fault bit indicates that a base page with the remote fault bit set has been received from the link partner. Once this bit goes high it latches high until it is unlatched by reading.

BitFields.Name: AutonegDone
BitFields.Documentation: The auto-negotiation complete bit indicates that the auto-negotiation process has been completed.

BitFields.Name: MfPreamSupAble
BitFields.Documentation:
The management frame preamble suppression ability bit always reads as 1'b1 to indicate that the PHY is able to receive management frames which are not preceded by the preamble pattern. However note that the first management frame after a H/W or S/W reset must have a full preamble so as to allow the PHY to synchronize to the station management.

The use of management frames without preamble is not generally recommended. If such frames are used then the MDIO synchronization lost interrupt bit should be monitored.

BitFields.Name: UnidirAble
BitFields.Documentation: The unidirectional ability register always reads as 1'b0 to indicate that the PHY can only transmit data from the MII when it has determined that a valid link has been established.

BitFields.Name: ExtStatSprt
BitFields.Documentation: The extended status support bit always reads as 1'b1 to indicate that the PHY provides extended status information in register 15.

BitFields.Name: HdT2Sprt
BitFields.Documentation: The 100BASE-T2 half duplex ability bit always reads as 1'b0 to indicate that the PHY does not support this technology.

BitFields.Name: FdT2Sprt
BitFields.Documentation: The 100BASE-T2 full duplex ability bits always reads as 1'b0 to indicate that the PHY does not support this technology.

BitFields.Name: Hd10Sprt
BitFields.Documentation: The 10 Mb/s half duplex ability bit indicates that the PHY supports this technology.

BitFields.Name: Fd10Sprt
BitFields.Documentation: The 10 Mb/s full duplex ability bit indicates that the PHY supports this technology.

BitFields.Name: Hd100Sprt
BitFields.Documentation: The 100BASE-X half duplex ability bit indicates that the PHY supports this technology.

BitFields.Name: Fd100Sprt
BitFields.Documentation: The 100BASE-X full duplex ability bit indicates that the PHY supports this technology.

BitFields.Name: T4Sprt
BitFields.Documentation: The 100BASE-T4 ability bit always reads as 1'b0 to indicate that the PHY does not support this technology.

Registers.Name: PhyId1
Registers.Documentation: The PHY ID 1 address allows 16 bits of the OUI to be observed.

BitFields.Name: PhyId1
BitFields.Documentation: The PHY ID 1 address allows 16 bits of the OUI to be observed.

Registers.Name: PhyId2
Registers.Documentation: The PHY ID 2 address allows 6 bits of the OUI along with the model number and revision number to be observed. The individual fields are broken out in the following rows.

BitFields.Name: RevNum
BitFields.Documentation: The revision number field allows the device revision number to be observed.

BitFields.Name: ModelNum
BitFields.Documentation: The model number field allows the device model number to be observed.

BitFields.Name: PhyId2Oui
BitFields.Documentation: The 6 MSBs of the PHY ID 2 address allow 6 bits of the OUI to be observed.

Registers.Name: AutonegAdv
Registers.Documentation: This address corresponds to the auto-negotiation advertisement register specified in clause 22.2.4.1.3 of Std 802.3.

BitFields.Name: SelectorAdv
BitFields.Documentation: The selector advertisement register always reads as 5'b00001 as the PHY only supports 802.3.

BitFields.Name: Hd10Adv
BitFields.Documentation: The 10BASE-T half duplex advertisement register indicates that this technology should be advertised to the link partner.

BitFields.Name: Fd10Adv
BitFields.Documentation: The 10BASE-T full duplex advertisement register indicates that this technology should be advertised to the link partner.

BitFields.Name: Hd100Adv
BitFields.Documentation: The 100BASE-TX half duplex advertisement register indicates that this technology should be advertised to the link partner.

BitFields.Name: Fd100Adv
BitFields.Documentation: The 100BASE-TX full duplex advertisement register indicates that this technology should be advertised to the link partner.

BitFields.Name: T4Adv
BitFields.Documentation: The 100BASE-T4 advertisement bit always reads as 1'b0 as this technology is not supported.

BitFields.Name: PauseAdv
BitFields.Documentation: The pause advertisement register indicates that support for pause operation on full duplex links should be advertised to the link partner.

BitFields.Name: ApauseAdv
BitFields.Documentation: The asymmetric pause advertisement register indicates that support for asymmetric pause operation on full duplex links should be advertised to the link partner.

BitFields.Name: ExtNextPageAdv
BitFields.Documentation: The extended next page advertisement register indicates that support for Extended Next Pages should be advertised to the link partner. Note that when set, optimized FLP burst timing is used

BitFields.Name: RemFltAdv
BitFields.Documentation: The remote fault advertisement register indicates that the remote fault bit of the base link codeword should be set to 1'b1 so as to signal a fault to the link partner.

BitFields.Name: NextPageAdv
BitFields.Documentation: The next page advertisement register indicates that the PHY wishes to send an additional next page to the link partner. Additional next pages are those that are sent after any next pages that are required by the standard auto-negotiation process.

Registers.Name: LpAbility
Registers.Documentation: This address corresponds to the link partner ability register specified in clause 28.2.4.1.4 of Std 802.3.

BitFields.Name: LpSelector
BitFields.Documentation: The link partner selector field indicates how the link partner technology abilities should be interpreted. The value 5'b00001 corresponds to 802.3.

BitFields.Name: LpHd10Able
BitFields.Documentation: The link partner 10BASE-T half duplex ability bit indicates that this technology is supported by the link partner.

BitFields.Name: LpFd10Able
BitFields.Documentation: The link partner 10BASE-T full duplex ability bit indicates that this technology is supported by the link partner.

BitFields.Name: LpHd100Able
BitFields.Documentation: The link partner 100BASE-TX half duplex ability bit indicates that this technology is supported by the link partner.

BitFields.Name: LpFd100Able
BitFields.Documentation: The link partner 100BASE-TX full duplex ability bit indicates that this technology is supported by the link partner.

BitFields.Name: LpT4Able
BitFields.Documentation: The link partner 100BASE-T4 ability bit indicates that this technology is supported by the link partner.

BitFields.Name: LpPauseAble
BitFields.Documentation: The link partner pause ability bit indicates that the link partner supports pause operation on full duplex links.

BitFields.Name: LpApauseAble
BitFields.Documentation: The link partner asymmetric pause ability bit indicates that the link partner supports asymmetric pause operation on full duplex links.

BitFields.Name: LpExtNextPageAble
BitFields.Documentation: The link partner extended next page bit indicates that lthe link partner supports extended next pages

BitFields.Name: LpRemFlt
BitFields.Documentation: The link partner remote fault bit indicates that a remote fault was signalled by the link partner.

BitFields.Name: LpNextPage
BitFields.Documentation: The link partner next page bit indicates that the link partner wishes to send a next page.

Registers.Name: AutonegExp
Registers.Documentation: This address corresponds to the auto-negotiation expansion register specified in clause 28.2.4.1.5 of Std 802.3.

BitFields.Name: LpAutonegAble
BitFields.Documentation: The link partner auto-negotiation ability bit indicates that the link partner supports auto-negotiation.

BitFields.Name: PageRxLat
BitFields.Documentation: The page received bit indicates that a new link codeword has been received. Once this bit goes high it latches high until it is unlatched by reading.

BitFields.Name: NpAble
BitFields.Documentation: The next page ability bit always reads as 1'b1 indicating that the PHY supports next pages.

BitFields.Name: LpNpAble
BitFields.Documentation: The link partner next page ability bit indicates that the link partner supports next pages.

BitFields.Name: ParDetFlt
BitFields.Documentation: The parallel detection fault bit indicates that a fault was detected during parallel detection. Once this bit goes high it latches high until it is unlatched by reading.

BitFields.Name: RxNpLoc
BitFields.Documentation: The received next page location bit always reads as 1'b1 indicating that received next pages are stored at address 8.

BitFields.Name: RxNpLocAble
BitFields.Documentation: The received next page location ability bit always reads as 1'b1 indicating that the PHY provides a received next page location bit.

Registers.Name: TxNextPage
Registers.Documentation: This address corresponds to the auto-negotiation next page transmit register specified in clause 28.2.4.1.6 of std 802.3.

BitFields.Name: NpCode
BitFields.Documentation: The next page message/unformatted code register contains the data portion of the next page.

BitFields.Name: NpToggle
BitFields.Documentation: The next page toggle bit is generated by the PHY in such a way as to ensure that two consecutive next pages cannot be identical.

BitFields.Name: NpAck2
BitFields.Documentation: The next page acknowledge 2 register indicates that the PHY is able to comply with the message that it is acknowledging.

BitFields.Name: NpMsgPage
BitFields.Documentation: The next page message page register indicates that the next page contains a predefined message code.

BitFields.Name: NpNextPage
BitFields.Documentation: The next page register indicates that the PHY wishes to send a subsequent next page.

Registers.Name: LpRxNextPage
Registers.Documentation: This address corrresponds to the auto-negotiation link partner received next page register specified in clause 28.2.4.1.7 of Std 802.3.

BitFields.Name: LpNpCode
BitFields.Documentation: The link partner next page message/unformatted code register contains the data portion of the next page.

BitFields.Name: LpNpToggle
BitFields.Documentation: The link partner next page toggle bit is generated by the link partner in such a way as to ensure that two consecutive next pages cannot be identical.

BitFields.Name: LpNpAck2
BitFields.Documentation: The link partner next page acknowledge 2 register indicates that the link partner is able to comply with the message that it is acknowledging.

BitFields.Name: LpNpMsgPage
BitFields.Documentation: The link partner next page message page register indicates that the next page contains a predefined message code.

BitFields.Name: LpNpNextPage
BitFields.Documentation: The link partner next page register indicates that the link partner wishes to send a subsequent next page.

Registers.Name: MstrSlvControl
Registers.Documentation: This address corrresponds to the MASTER-SLAVE Control register specified in Std 802.3.

BitFields.Name: Hd1000Adv
BitFields.Documentation: The 1000BASE-T half duplex advertisement register indicates that this technology should be advertised to the link partner.

BitFields.Name: Fd1000Adv
BitFields.Documentation: The 1000BASE-T full duplex advertisement register indicates that this technology should be advertised to the link partner.

BitFields.Name: PrefMstrAdv
BitFields.Documentation: The prefer master (or port type) advertisement register indicates that the PHY should advertise that it would prefer to operate as master (or is in a multi-port system). This advertisement will be ignored if ManMstrSlvEnAdv is set.

BitFields.Name: ManMstrAdv
BitFields.Documentation: The manual master advertisement register indicates that the PHY should advertise that it is manually configured as master. This register determines whether the PHY is configured as master or slave when ManMstrSlvEnAdv is set.

BitFields.Name: ManMstrSlvEnAdv
BitFields.Documentation: The manual master /slave enable advertisment register indicates that the PHY should advertise that its master/slave configuration is manually configured.

BitFields.Name: TstMode
BitFields.Documentation: The test mode register allows the test modes specified in clause 40.6.1.1.2 of std 802.3 to be enabled.

Registers.Name: MstrSlvStatus
Registers.Documentation: This address corrresponds to the MASTER-SLAVE Status register specified in Std 802.3.

BitFields.Name: IdleErrCnt
BitFields.Documentation: This field corresponds to the idle error counter specified in clause 40.5.1.1 of std 802.3.

BitFields.Name: LpHd1000Able
BitFields.Documentation: The link partner 1000BASE-T half duplex ability bit indicates that this technology is supported by the link partner.

BitFields.Name: LpFd1000Able
BitFields.Documentation: The link partner 1000BASE-T full duplex ability bit indicates that this technology is supported by the link partner.

BitFields.Name: RemRcvrStatus
BitFields.Documentation: The remote receiver status bit reads as 1'b1 when the rem_rcvr_status variable specified in clause 40.4.5.1 of std 802.3 is OK.

BitFields.Name: LocRcvrStatus
BitFields.Documentation: The local receiver status bit reads as 1'b1 when the loc_rcvr_status variable specified in clause 40.4.5.1 of std 802.3 is OK.

BitFields.Name: MstrRslvd
BitFields.Documentation: The master/slave configuration resolution bit reads as 1'b1 to indicate that the local PHY resolved to master.

BitFields.Name: MstrSlvFlt
BitFields.Documentation:
The master/slave configuration fault bit indicates that master/slave was not successfully resolved. Once this bit goes high it latches high until it is unlatched by reading.

The MstrSlvFlt bit is automatically cleared when auto-negotiation is enabled or when the auto-negotiation process completes.

Registers.Name: ExtStatus
Registers.Documentation: This address corresponds to the extended status register specified in clause 22.2.4.4 of Std 802.3.

BitFields.Name: Hd1000Sprt
BitFields.Documentation: The 1000BASE-T half duplex ability bit indicates that the PHY supports this technology.

BitFields.Name: Fd1000Sprt
BitFields.Documentation: The 1000BASE-T full duplex ability bit indicates that the PHY supports this technology.

BitFields.Name: Hd1000XSprt
BitFields.Documentation: The 1000BASE-X half duplex ability bit always reads as 1'b0 to indicate that the PHY does not support this technology.

BitFields.Name: Fd1000XSprt
BitFields.Documentation: The 1000BASE-X full duplex ability bit always reads as 1'b0 to indicate that the PHY does not support this technology.

Registers.Name: ExtRegPtr
Registers.Documentation:
The extended register pointer and data addresses provide a mechanism to allow the station management to access the indirect access address map via directly accessible registers.

Writing to ExtRegPtr indicates that the management frame payload corresponds to a register address in the configurable MMD device of the indirect access address map. Once this register address has been specified it can be read or written by reading or writing ExtRegData.

BitFields.Name: ExtRegPtr
BitFields.Documentation:
The extended register pointer and data addresses provide a mechanism to allow the station management to access the indirect access address map via directly accessible registers.

Writing to ExtRegPtr indicates that the management frame payload corresponds to a register address in the configurable MMD device of the indirect access address map. Once this register address has been specified it can be read or written by reading or writing ExtRegData.

Registers.Name: ExtRegData
Registers.Documentation: See ExtRegPtr

BitFields.Name: ExtRegData
BitFields.Documentation: See ExtRegPtr

Registers.Name: PhyCtrl1
Registers.Documentation: This address provides access to various PHY control registers, in particular for diagnostic clocking control and MDI crossover.

BitFields.Name: PwrMngEn
BitFields.Documentation:
The power management enable register allows the smart power management features of the PHY such as clock gating to be controlled.

Clearing this bit is not generally recommended.

BitFields.Name: DiagClkEn
BitFields.Documentation: The diagnostics clock enable register allows the PHY diagnostics clock to be switched on in order to use the built-in diagnostics features of the PHY.

BitFields.Name: ManMdix
BitFields.Documentation: The manual MDI-X configuration register allows the PHY MDI/MDI-X configuration to be manually controlled when AutoMdiEn is clear.

BitFields.Name: AutoMdiEn
BitFields.Documentation: The automatic MDI/MDI-X resolution enable register allows the automatic cable crossover feature of the PHY to be controlled. When this bit is clear the MDI/MDI-X configuration is determined by the ManMdix register.

BitFields.Name: ManMdiFlip
BitFields.Documentation: The manual MDI flip register allows the order of the PHY dimensions to be reversed in order to accomodate alternative board layouts.

BitFields.Name: RxErrCntCfg
BitFields.Documentation:
The receive error counter configuration register allows the error conditions counted by RxErrCnt to be controlled as follows:

  2'b00: Count CRCs
  2'b01: Count symbol errors
  2'b10: Count CRCs and false carrier events 
  2'b11: Count symbol errors and false carrier events

Note that RxErrCnt is not automatically cleared when RxErrCntCfg is written.

BitFields.Name: RslvMdiManSpeed
BitFields.Documentation:
When set this register requires the PHY to resolve the MDI/MDI-X configuration before enabling the selected technology when the speed is manually selected.

Clearing this bit is not recommended.

Registers.Name: PhyCtrlStatus1
Registers.Documentation: This address provides access to various PHY control and status registers, in particular PHY loopback controls and auto-negotiation status bits.

BitFields.Name: LbMiiLsOk
BitFields.Documentation: The MII loopback link status is OK register allows the link status to be controlled by software when performing MII loopback. The reason for providing this register is that the MII loopback is so shallow that there is no physical layer circuitry at all involved in it which means that there is no natural driver for the link status signal.

BitFields.Name: FlpLnkGoodChng
BitFields.Documentation:
The flp_link_good variable changed bit is set whenever there is a change in the associated variable. The flp_link_good variable is controlled by the auto-negotiation arbitration state machine specified in clause 28.3.4 of std 802.3.

Once this bit goes high it latches high until it is unlatched by reading.

This bit is provided to allow the station management to observe the progess of auto-negotiation in more detail.

BitFields.Name: SnglLnkRdyChng
BitFields.Documentation:
The single_link_ready variable changed bit is set whenever there is a change in the associated variable. The single_link_ready variable is specified in clause 28.3.1 of std 802.3.

Once this bit goes high it latches high until it is unlatched by reading.

This bit is provided to allow the station management to observe the progess of auto-negotiation in more detail.

BitFields.Name: FlpRcvIdleChng
BitFields.Documentation:
The flp_receive_idle variable changed bit is set whenever there is a change in the associated variable. The flp_receive_idle variable is controlled by the auto-negotiation receive state machine specified in clause 28.3.4 of std 802.3. Once this bit goes high it latches high until it is unlatched by reading.

This bit is provided to allow the station management to observe the progess of auto-negotiation in more detail.

BitFields.Name: AnegDoneChng
BitFields.Documentation:
The mr_autoneg_complete variable changed bit is set whenever there is a change in the associated variable. The mr_autoneg_complete variable is controlled by the auto-negotiation arbitration state machine specified in clause 28.3.4 of std 802.3.

Once this bit goes high it latches high until it is unlatched by reading.

This bit is provided to allow the station management to observe the progess of auto-negotiation in more detail.

BitFields.Name: LbTxSup
BitFields.Documentation:
The suppress transmit in loopback register determines whether or not the PHY should transmit a signal to the line during loopback. This register has no effect unless the all-digital loopback mode is  enabled.

When the PHY is in the all-digital loopback mode and this bit is clear a valid signal will be transmitted to the line but no receive signal will be required.

BitFields.Name: LbExtEn
BitFields.Documentation: The external loopback enable register allows the PHY to be configured for external loopback. In this loopback configuration an external connection must be provided between pairs 0 and 1 and pairs 2 and 3.

BitFields.Name: IsolateRx
BitFields.Documentation: The isolate receive register allows the receive data stream from the PHY to the ASIC core to be suppressed.

BitFields.Name: LbRemoteEn
BitFields.Documentation:
The remote loopback enable register allows the PHY to be configured for remote loopback. In this loopback configuration a link is established with the link partner in the normal way but the PHY loops any data that it receives back to its transmitter.

If the IsolateRx register is clear then the PHY will also pass any data that it receives on to the ASIC core. If the IsolateRx register is set then the PHY will not send any data to the ASIC core.

BitFields.Name: LbLdSel
BitFields.Documentation:
The line driver loopback select register may be used to associate line driver loopback mode with the Loopback bit. If this register is set then every time the Loopback bit is set the PHY will enter its line driver loopback mode.

In line driver loopback the MDI pins should be left open so as to create a large impedance mismatch. The PHY can then operate by receiving the reflection from its own transmission.

BitFields.Name: LbAllDigSel
BitFields.Documentation:
The all digital loopback select register may be used to associate all digital loopback mode with the Loopback bit. If this register is set then every time the Loopback bit is set the PHY will enter its all digital loopback mode.

In all digital loopback mode the PHY loops any data that is transmitted back to the receive side at the analog interface. If the LbTxSup register is set then this loopback generates no signal at the MDI pins and can be performed without disturbing a link partner that may be present. If the LbTxSup register is clear then the transmit signal may be observed at the MDI pins.

BitFields.Name: LbMiiSel
BitFields.Documentation:
The MII loopback select register may be used to associate MII loopback mode with the Loopback bit. If this register is set then every time the Loopback bit is set the PHY will enter its MII loopback mode.

In MII loopback mode the PHY loops any data that is transmitted back to the receive side at the MII interface. As there is no physical layer circuitry at all involved in this loopback a link will be established very quickly making it ideal for checking the connectivity between the ASIC core and the PHY.

Registers.Name: RxErrCnt
Registers.Documentation: The receive error counter address may be used to access the associated counter. This counter may be configured to count a number of different combinations of error conditions by using the RxErrCntCfg register .

BitFields.Name: RxErrCnt
BitFields.Documentation: The receive error counter address may be used to access the associated counter. This counter may be configured to count a number of different combinations of error conditions by using the RxErrCntCfg register .

Registers.Name: PhyCtrlStatus2
Registers.Documentation: This address provides access to various PHY control and status registers, in particular auto-negotiation controls and energy-detect powerdown control and status bits.

BitFields.Name: AnegTo1000Dis
BitFields.Documentation: The disable auto-negotiation to 1000BASE-T register may be used to prevent the PHY from advertising either half duplex or full duplex 1000BASE-T ability.

BitFields.Name: PhyInNrgPd
BitFields.Documentation: The PHY is in energy detect powerdown bit indicates that the PHY has switched into its energy detect powerdown mode. In this mode the PHY configures itself for minimum power consumption while monitoring the line for energy. If energy is detected then the PHY exits the energy detect powerdown mode and attempts to establish a link.

BitFields.Name: NrgPdTxEn
BitFields.Documentation: The enable transmit while in energy detect powerdown register allows the PHY to be configured to ocassionally transmit a single pulse on both dimension 0 and dimension 1 while it is in energy detect powerdown. The idea is to avoid the lock-up condition that could otherwise arise if the PHYs at either end of a link were both in energy detect powerdown.

BitFields.Name: NrgPdEn
BitFields.Documentation: The energy detect powerdown enable register may be used to enable or disable the PHY from switching into its energy detect powerdown mode.

BitFields.Name: AnegTo100Dis
BitFields.Documentation: The disable auto-negotiation to 100BASE-TX register may be used to prevent the PHY from advertising either half duplex or full duplex 100BASE-TX ability.

BitFields.Name: NrgDetDim01
BitFields.Documentation: The energy detected on dimension 0 or 1 bit indicates that the PHY has detected signal energy on one or both of these dimensions. Once this bit goes high it remains high until the energy detect circuit/s that triggered it is/are disabled.

BitFields.Name: NrgDetDim23
BitFields.Documentation: The energy detected on dimension 2 or 3 bit indicates that the PHY has detected signal energy on one or both of these dimensions. Once this bit goes high it remains high until the energy detect circuit/s that triggered it is/are disabled.

Registers.Name: PhyCtrl2
Registers.Documentation: This address provides access to various PHY control registers, for control of clocking, group MDIO access, and auto-negotiation.

BitFields.Name: ClkCntrl
BitFields.Documentation: The clock control register allows the desired speed of the TX_CLK and RX_CLK signals to be specified when the link is down and allows the desired speed of the TX_CLK signal to be specified when a 1000BASE-T link is active. In each case the choices of speed are off, 2.5MHz and 25MHz. The default value of 3'b100 specifies 2.5MHz in all cases.

BitFields.Name: SysClkEn
BitFields.Documentation:
The system clock enable register may be used to enable the 125MHz system clock output from the PHY. The system clock is a permanently available 125MHz clock.

When this bit is set the PHY PLL is kept powered up all the time. This increases power consumption especially in the low-power modes of operation. It also prevents the PLL from being re-initialized when the PHY is reset.

Setting this bit is not recommended.

BitFields.Name: TstClkEn
BitFields.Documentation: The test clock enabled register may be used to enable the test clock output from the PHY. The PHY can output either its free-running clock or its recovered clock depending on the TclkFreeSel indirectly accessed register. By default the recovered clock is selected which corresponds to the transmit clock in 1000BASE-T.

BitFields.Name: GroupMdioEn
BitFields.Documentation:
The group MDIO enable register may be used to place the PHY in group MDIO mode. In this mode the PHY will respond to any write or address operation to PHY address 5'd31 as if it was an access to its own PHY address.

This feature is intended to allow initialization sequences in multi-port devices to be implemented more efficiently. It is recommended  that this bit be set only while performing specific sequences and then be cleared again.

BitFields.Name: UpSpeedTo1000En
BitFields.Documentation:
The upspeed to 1000BASE-T enable register determines whether or not the PHY is allowed to upspeed to 1000BASE-T when reverse auto-negotiating. Irrespective of this setting the PHY will not upspeed to 1000BASE-T unless 1000BASE-T advertisement is allowed.

See RevAnegEn for further information on reverse auto-negotiation.

BitFields.Name: UpSpeedTo100En
BitFields.Documentation:
The upspeed to 100BASE-TX enable register determines whether or not the PHY is allowed to upspeed to 100BASE-TX when reverse auto-negotiating. Irrespective of this setting the PHY will not upspeed to 100BASE-TX unless 100BASE-TX half or full duplex advertisement is allowed and the link partner has advertised a compatible 100BASE-TX ability.

See RevAnegEn for further information on reverse auto-negotiation.

BitFields.Name: DnSpeedTo10En
BitFields.Documentation: The downspeed to 10BASE-T enable register determines whether or not the PHY is allowed to downspeed to 10BASE-T when auto-negotiating. Irrespective of this setting the PHY will not downspeed to 10BASE-T unless 10BASE-T half or full duplex advertisement is allowed and the link partner has advertised a compatible 10BASE-T ability.

BitFields.Name: DnSpeedTo100En
BitFields.Documentation: The downspeed to 100BASE-TX enable register determines whether or not the PHY is allowed to downspeed to 100BASE-TX when auto-negotiating. Irrespective of this setting the PHY will not downspeed to 100BASE-TX unless 100BASE-TX half or full duplex advertisement is allowed and the link partner has advertised a compatible 100BASE-TX ability.

BitFields.Name: HdTxCrsEn
BitFields.Documentation: When set this register indicates that the PHY should assert  CRS on transmit in half duplex mode.

Registers.Name: PhyCtrl3
Registers.Documentation: This address provides access to various PHY control registers, for link enable, energy-detect powerdown, and 10BASE-T and auto-negotiation controls.

BitFields.Name: ForceIrq
BitFields.Documentation: The force interrupt request register may be used to force the interrupt request to be asserted for test purposes.

BitFields.Name: NrgDetEn
BitFields.Documentation: The energy detection enable register may be used to enable the PHY receive channel energy detectors. When this register is set the bits NrgDetDim01 and NrgDetDim23 indicate if energy has been detected.

BitFields.Name: B10PreamLen
BitFields.Documentation:
The 10BASE-T preamble length register allows the number of bytes of preamble that are to be prepended to each receive frame to be specified in accordance with the following encoding:

  2'b00  No preamble
  2'b01  Preamble of 1 byte
  2'b10  Preamble of 2 bytes
  2'b11 Preamble of 7 bytes

Note that the preamble of 7 bytes represents a full 10BASE-T preamble. This setting is provided for cases where the received data is looped directly back to the transmitter.

BitFields.Name: B10HdMauLbEn
BitFields.Documentation: The 10BASE-T half duplex MAU loopback enable register indicates that the PHY should implement the MAU loopback function specified in clause 14.2.1.3 of Std 802.3.

BitFields.Name: B10SqeEn
BitFields.Documentation: The 10BASE-T SQE enable register indicates that the PHY should implement the SQE test function specified in clause 14.2.1.5 of Std 802.3.

BitFields.Name: B10JabberEn
BitFields.Documentation: The 10BASE-T jabber enable register indicates that the PHY should implement the jabber function specified in clause 14.2.1.6 of Std 802.3.

BitFields.Name: RevAnegEn
BitFields.Documentation: The reverse auto-negotiation enable register may be used to indicate to the PHY that it should attempt to auto-negotiate to the lowest possible speed. This is achieved by initially not advertising the higher speeds.

BitFields.Name: UpSpeedRetryEn
BitFields.Documentation: When set this register indicates to the PHY that during the reverse auto-negotiation process it should retry each lower speed before upspeeding to the next lowest available speed. In this case the number of retries at each speed is controlled by the NumSpeedRetry register.

BitFields.Name: NumSpeedRetry
BitFields.Documentation:
During the normal auto-negotiation process this register determines how many retries the PHY should allow at each speed before downspeeding. Add 1 to the value specified to get the total number of auto-negotiation attempts at each speed.

During the reverse auto-negotiation process if UpSpeedRetryEn is set then this register determines how many retries the PHY should allow at each speed before upspeeding.

BitFields.Name: LinkEn
BitFields.Documentation: The link enable register indicates that the PHY should attempt to establish a link if there is a link partner present. If this bit is cleared then the PHY will take down any active link and go into its standby mode. In this mode the PHY will not respond to link pulses from the link partner. However the cable monitoring features may be used.

Registers.Name: IrqMask
Registers.Documentation: The interrupt mask register allows interrupts to be masked or unmasked.

BitFields.Name: HwIrqEn
BitFields.Documentation: When set this register indicates that the PHY should assert the hardware interrupt request signal in response to any pending  interrupt.

BitFields.Name: SpeedChngIrqEn
BitFields.Documentation: When set this register enables the speed change interrupt. This interrupt is triggered when the PHY upspeeds or downspeeds.

BitFields.Name: LnkStatChngIrqEn
BitFields.Documentation: When set this register enables the link status change interrupt. This interrupt is triggered when the link status changes.

BitFields.Name: RxStatChngIrqEn
BitFields.Documentation: When set this register enables the receive status change interrupt. This interrupt is triggered when the local or remote receive status changes.

BitFields.Name: FifoOuIrqEn
BitFields.Documentation: When set this register enables the transmit  FIFO overflow/underflow interrupt.

BitFields.Name: IdleErrCntIrqEn
BitFields.Documentation: When set this register enables the idle error counter interrupt. This interrupt triggers when the IdleErrCnt is saturated.

BitFields.Name: PageRxIrqEn
BitFields.Documentation: When set this register enables the page received interrupt. This interrupt triggers on a rising edge of the mr_page_rx variable specified in clause 28.3.1 of Std 802.3.

BitFields.Name: FcFgIrqEn
BitFields.Documentation:
When set this register enables the frame checker/generator interrupt. This interrupt may trigger when the frame checker detects an error or when the frame generator completes an operation.

See the vendor GMII/MII registers in the indirect access address map for more information on frame checker/generator interrupts.

BitFields.Name: AnStatChngIrqEn
BitFields.Documentation: When set this register enables the auto-negotiation status change interrupt. This interrupt triggers in response to certain changes in the auto-negotiation status. The changes that can trigger this interrupt are individually tracked by the bits FlpLnkGoodChng, FlpLnkGoodChng, FlpRcvIdleChng and AnegDoneChng.

BitFields.Name: MdioSyncIrqEn
BitFields.Documentation:
When set this register enables the MDIO synchronization lost interrupt. This interrupt triggers when the PHY detects that synchronization has been lost at the management interface.

This interrupt should be monitored when using management frames without a full preamble.

BitFields.Name: CblMonIrqEn
BitFields.Documentation: When set this register enables the cable monitoring interrupt. This interrupt triggers in response to changes in the status of the cable monitoring module.

BitFields.Name: FfeCanAccIrqEn
BitFields.Documentation:
When set this register enables the FFE/canceller access interrupt. This interrupt triggers when access to the FFE or canceller coefficients is is given or taken away.

See the vendor FFE and cancellers registers in the indirect access address map  for more information on coefficient access.

BitFields.Name: AdcSmpRdyIrqEn
BitFields.Documentation:
When set this register enables the ADC sample ready interrupt. This interrupt triggers when the ADC sampling circuit has captured a sample.

See the vendor AFE control registers in the indirect access address map  for more information on ADC sampling.

BitFields.Name: DiagAluRdyIrq
BitFields.Documentation:
When set this register enables the diagnostics ALU ready interrupt. Ths interupt triggers when a result is available from the diagnostics ALU.
