See the vendor diagnostics ALU registers in the indirect access address map  for more information.

BitFields.Name: SvrIrqEn
BitFields.Documentation:
When set this register enables the state vector redirect interrupt. This interrupt triggers when a PMA control or adaptation control state vector redirect operation is done.

See the vendor PMA control and adaptation control registers in the indirect address map for more information on state vector redirect operations.

BitFields.Name: NrgDetIrqEn
BitFields.Documentation: When set this register enables the energy detect interrupt. This interrupt is triggered when either NrgDetDim01 or NrgDetDim23 goes high.

Registers.Name: IrqStatus
Registers.Documentation: The interrupt status address may be used to check which interrupts have triggered since the last time it was read. Each bit will go high when the associated interrupt triggers and will then latch high until it is unlatched by reading. The bits of IrqStatus go high even when the associated interrupts are not enabled. However only bits associated with enabled interrupts are considered when generating the IrqPending indication.

BitFields.Name: IrqPending
BitFields.Documentation: The IrqPending bit indicates that an interrupt request is pending. Only enabled interrupts contribute to the generation of IrqPending. When the HwIrqEn register is set the hardware interrupt signal is asserted if IrqPending is set.

BitFields.Name: SpeedChngIrqStat
BitFields.Documentation: The speed change interrupt status bit indicates that the associated interrupt triggered since IrqStatus was last read.

BitFields.Name: LnkStatChngIrqStat
BitFields.Documentation: The link status change interrupt status bit indicates that the associated interrupt triggered since IrqStatus was last read.

BitFields.Name: RxStatChngIrqStat
BitFields.Documentation: The receive status change interrupt status bit indicates that the associated interrupt triggered since IrqStatus was last read.

BitFields.Name: FifoOuIrqStat
BitFields.Documentation: The transmit  FIFO overflow/underflow interrupt status bit indicates that the associated interrupt triggered since IrqStatus was last read.

BitFields.Name: IdleErrCntIrqStat
BitFields.Documentation: The idle error counter interrupt status bit indicates that the associated interrupt triggered since IrqStatus was last read.

BitFields.Name: PageRxIrqStat
BitFields.Documentation: The page received interrupt status bit indicates that the associated interrupt triggered since IrqStatus was last read.

BitFields.Name: FcFgIrqStat
BitFields.Documentation: The frame checker/generator interrupt status bit indicates that the associated interrupt triggered since IrqStatus was last read.

BitFields.Name: AnStatChngIrqStat
BitFields.Documentation: The auto-negotiation status change interrupt status bit indicates that the associated interrupt triggered since IrqStatus was last read.

BitFields.Name: MdioSyncIrqStat
BitFields.Documentation: The MDIO synchronization lost interrupt status bit indicates that the associated interrupt triggered since IrqStatus was last read.

BitFields.Name: CblMonIrqStat
BitFields.Documentation: The cable monitoring interrupt status bit indicates that the associated interrupt triggered since IrqStatus was last read.

BitFields.Name: FfeCanAccIrqStat
BitFields.Documentation: The FFE/canceller access interrupt status bit indicates that the associated interrupt triggered since IrqStatus was last read.

BitFields.Name: AdcSmpRdyIrqStat
BitFields.Documentation: The ADC sample ready interrupt status bit indicates that the associated interrupt triggered since IrqStatus was last read.

BitFields.Name: DiagAluRdyStat
BitFields.Documentation: The diagnostics ALU ready interrupt status bit indicates that the associated interrupt triggered since IrqStatus was last read.

BitFields.Name: SvrIrqStat
BitFields.Documentation: The state vector redirect interrupt status bit indicates that the associated interrupt triggered since IrqStatus was last read.

BitFields.Name: NrgDetIrqStat
BitFields.Documentation: The energy detect interrupt status bit indicates that the associated interrupt triggered since IrqStatus was last read.

Registers.Name: PhyStatus1
Registers.Documentation: This address provides access to various PHY status registers.

BitFields.Name: LpApauseAdv
BitFields.Documentation:
The link partner asymmetric pause advertisement bit indicates that the link partner advertised support for asymmetric pause operation on full duplex links.

This bit provides the same information as LpApauseAble.

BitFields.Name: LpPauseAdv
BitFields.Documentation:
The link partner pause advertisement bit indicates that the link partner advertised support for pause operation on full duplex links.

This bit provides the same information as LpPauseAble.

BitFields.Name: AutonegSup
BitFields.Documentation: The auto-negotiation supported bit reads as 1'b1 when both AutonegEn and LpAutonegAble are asserted.

BitFields.Name: ColStat
BitFields.Documentation: The collision status bit reads as 1'b1 when the GMII/MII COL signal is asserted.

BitFields.Name: RxDvStat
BitFields.Documentation: The receive data valid status bit reads as 1'b1 when the GMII/MII RX_DV signal is asserted.

BitFields.Name: TxEnStat
BitFields.Documentation: The transmit enable status bit reads as 1'b1 when the GMII/MII TX_EN signal is asserted.

BitFields.Name: LinkStat
BitFields.Documentation:
The link status bit reads as 1'b1 when the relevant technology dependent link_status signal is OK.

This bit provides the same information as LinkStatLat except that it does not latch low.

BitFields.Name: HcdTech
BitFields.Documentation:
The highest common denominator technology field allows the resolved technology to be determined in accordance with the following encoding:

  3'd0  10BASE-T half duplex
  3'd1  10BASE-T full duplex
  3'd2  100BASE-TX half duplex
  3'd3  100BASE-TX full duplex
  3'd4  1000BASE-T half duplex
  3'd5  1000BASE-T full duplex
  3'd6  Not determined

Once a link is established this field correctly indicates the technology irrespective of how the link was established.

BitFields.Name: B10PolInv
BitFields.Documentation: The 10BASE-T polarity inverted bit indicates that the PHY has observed that the polarity of auto-negotation or 10BASE-T link pulses is inverted.

BitFields.Name: Pair01Swap
BitFields.Documentation:
The pairs 0 and 1 swapped bit indicates that the PHY has detected that dimensions 0 and 1 are swapped.

By convention the network is supposed to be designed so that pairs 0 and 1 are crossed once. If this is done then the PHY will receive on pair 1 the signal that is being transmitted by the link partner on pair 0. This is regarded as the normal configuration.

The PHY is able to detect the case where it is receiving on pair 0 the signal that is being transmitted by the link partner on pair 0. When this condition is detected Pair01Swap will be asserted.

BitFields.Name: AutonegStat
BitFields.Documentation: The auto-negotiation status bit is a copy of AutonegDone.

BitFields.Name: ParDetFltStat
BitFields.Documentation: The parallel detection fault status bit is a copy of ParDetFlt. Reading this copy does not unlatch the original.

BitFields.Name: MstrSlvFltStat
BitFields.Documentation: The master/slave configuration fault status bit is a copy of MstrSlvFlt. Reading this copy does not unlatch the original.

BitFields.Name: PhyInStndby
BitFields.Documentation: The PHY in standby bit indicates that the PHY  is in its standby mode. This mode can be entered by clearing LinkEn. In this mode the PHY will not respond to link pulses from the link partner. However the cable monitoring features may be used.

Registers.Name: LedCtrl1
Registers.Documentation: This address provides access to various PHY LEDs control registers.

BitFields.Name: LedPulStrEn
BitFields.Documentation: The LED pulse stretching enable register indicates that the PHY should stretch any pulses indicating transmit, receive or collision. Without stretching these pulses may be too short to cause a LED to light.

BitFields.Name: LedOeN
BitFields.Documentation: When clear the LED active low output enable register indicates that the LED outputs should be driven.

BitFields.Name: LedPulStrDurSel
BitFields.Documentation:
The LED pulse stretching duration selection register allows the pulse stretching feature to be configured in accordance with the following encoding:

  2'b00  Stretch pulses by 32ms
  2'b01  Stretch pulses by 64ms 
  2'b10  Stretch pulses by 104ms
  2'b11  Stretch pulses by user programmed amount

When LedPulStrDurSel is set to 2'b11 the LedPulStrDur register in the indirect address map determines the pulse stretching duration.

BitFields.Name: LedPatPauseDur
BitFields.Documentation:
The LED blink pattern pause duration field allows the delay between repetitions of the LED blink pattern to be programmed. This one field is associated with four separate LED blink pattern pause duration registers - one for each LED output. The LedPatSel register determines which of these registers is selected for read and write.

The last value in the blink pattern is held for the duration determined by this register. To determine this duration multiply the value specified by the LED blink pattern tick duration which is controlled by the associated LedPatTickDur register.

BitFields.Name: LedAExtCfgEn
BitFields.Documentation:
When this register is set LedACfg selects the LED A configuration from the extended LED configuration set in accordance with the following encoding:

  4'b0000  On if 10BASE-T or 100BASE-TX link
  4'b0001  On if 100BASE-TX or 1000BASE-T link
  4'b0010  On if 10BASE-T link, blink if activity
  4'b0011  On if 100BASE-TX link, blink if activity
  4'b0100  On if 1000BASE-T link, blink if activity
  4'b0101  On if 10BASE-T or 100BASE-TX link, blink if activity
  4'b0110  On if 100BASE-TX or 1000BASE-T link, blink if activity
  4'b0111  On if 10BASE-T or 1000BASE-T link
  4'b1000  On if 10BASE-T or 1000BASE-T link, blink if activity
  4'b1001  Blink if activity
  4'b1010  Blink if transmit
  4'b1011  On if 1000BASE-T link, blink if 10BASE-T link
  4'b1100  On if 100BASE-TX link, blink if 1000BASE-T link
  4'b1101  On if 100BASE-TX link, blink if 10BASE-T link
  4'b1110  On if 10BASE-T link, blink if 1000BASE-T link
  4'b1111  On if 10BASE-T link, blink if 100BASE-TX link

When LedAExtCfgEn is clear LedACfg selects the LED A configuration from the standard LED configuration set which is detailed under LedACfg.

BitFields.Name: LedBExtCfgEn
BitFields.Documentation: This register enables the extended LED configuration set for LED B. See LedAExtCfgEn for more information.

BitFields.Name: LedCExtCfgEn
BitFields.Documentation: This register enables the extended LED configuration set for LED C. See LedAExtCfgEn for more information.

BitFields.Name: LedDExtCfgEn
BitFields.Documentation: This register enables the extended LED configuration set for LED D. See LedAExtCfgEn for more information.

BitFields.Name: LedAB2ClrEn
BitFields.Documentation: The LED A/B 2-color mode enable register allows LED A and B to be configured for 2-color operation. In this case LED A is forced off when LED B is on.

BitFields.Name: LedCD2ClrEn
BitFields.Documentation: The LED C/D 2-color mode enable register allows LED C and D to be configured for 2-color operation. In this case LED C is forced off when LED D is on.

Registers.Name: LedCtrl2
Registers.Documentation: This address provides access to various PHY LEDs control registers.

BitFields.Name: LedACfg
BitFields.Documentation:
When LedAExtCfgEn is clear this register selects the LED A configuration from the standard LED configuration set in accordance with the following encoding:

  4'b0000  On if 1000BASE-T link
  4'b0001  On if 100BASE-TX link
  4'b0010  On if 10BASE-T link
  4'b0011  On if 1000BASE-T link, blink if 100BASE-TX link
  4'b0100  On if link
  4'b0101  On if transmitting
  4'b0110  On if receiving
  4'b0111  On if activity (transmitting or receiving)
  4'b1000  On if full duplex link
  4'b1001  On if collision
  4'b1010  On if link, blink if activity
  4'b1011  On if link, blink if receiving
  4'b1100  On if full duplex link, blink if collision
  4'b1101  Blink
  4'b1110  On
  4'b1111  Off

When LedAExtCfgEn is set LedACfg selects the LED A configuration from the extended LED configuration set which is described under LedAExtCfgEn.

BitFields.Name: LedBCfg
BitFields.Documentation: This register selects the configuration for LED B. See LedACfg for more information.

BitFields.Name: LedCCfg
BitFields.Documentation: This register selects the configuration for LED C. See LedACfg for more information.

BitFields.Name: LedDCfg
BitFields.Documentation: This register selects the configuration for LED D. See LedACfg for more information.

Registers.Name: LedCtrl3
Registers.Documentation: This address provides access to various PHY LEDs control registers.

BitFields.Name: LedPat
BitFields.Documentation:
The LED blink pattern field allows the blink pattern to be programmed. This one field is associated with four separate LED blink pattern registers - one for each LED output. The LedPatSel register determines which of these registers is selected for read and write.

Each bit in a pattern register indicates whether the associated LED is to be turned on or not. The bits are processed starting with the LSB and each bit is active for a duration determined by the associated LedPatTickDur register. After the last bit has been processed a pause determined by the corresponding LedPatPauseDur register is inserted and then the pattern is repeated.

BitFields.Name: LedPatTickDur
BitFields.Documentation:
The LED blink pattern tick duration allows the timebase for the blink pattern to be programmed. This one field is associated with four separate LED blink pattern tick duration registers - one for each LED output. The LedPatSel register determines which of these registers is selected for read and write.

Add 1 to the value specified and then multiply by 8 to determine the tick duration in ms. The value 6'd63 is a special value which sets the tick duration to 1ms.

BitFields.Name: LedPatSel
BitFields.Documentation:
The LED blink pattern select register allows management to specify which of the LED blink patterns it wishes to program in accordance with the following encoding:

  2'b00  LED A blink pattern
  2'b01  LED B blink pattern
  2'b10  LED C blink pattern
  2'b11  LED D blink pattern

The LedPatPauseDur, LedPat and LedPatTickDur fields indirectly access the corresponding registers for selected blink pattern.

Registers.Name: LateColCnt
Registers.Documentation:
This address provides access to the PHY's late collision counters.
See LateColCnt02 and LateColCnt13 for more details.

BitFields.Name: LateColCnt02
BitFields.Documentation:
When the PHY is operating in half duplex mode collisions may occur during bytes 0 to 63 of a transmit frame. Collisions occurring after that are counted by the late collision counters as follows:

  Late collision counter 0:  Collisions during bytes 64 - 95
  Late collision counter 1:  Collisions during bytes 96 - 127
  Late collision counter 2:  Collisions during bytes 128 - 191
  Late collision counter 3:  Collisions during bytes 192 - 319

If any counter saturates then all of the counters stop incrementing.

The profile of the late collision counters may be used to determine whether the late collisions are being caused by an overextended network topology or by a duplex mismatch.

To use the late collision counters the LateColCntEn register in the indirect access address map must be set.

See LateColCnt13 for information on reading the collision counters.

BitFields.Name: LateColCnt13
BitFields.Documentation:
See LateColCnt02 for information on using the collision counters.

Each of the late collision counters is 8 bits. They can be read two at a time. The LateColCnt02 field corresponds either to counter 0 or 2 and the LateColCnt13 field corresponds either to counter 1 or 3 depending on the value of LateColCnt23Sel.

When LateColCnt23Sel is clear counters 0 and 1 may be read. After reading counters 0 and 1 all of the counters stop incrementing and LateColCnt23Sel is set so as to allow counters 2 and 3 to be read. After reading counters 2 and 3 all of the counters are cleared and start incrementing once again and LateColCnt23Sel is cleared.

Registers.Name: PhyStatus2
Registers.Documentation: This address provides access to various PHY status registers.

BitFields.Name: B1000DscrAcqErr
BitFields.Documentation:
The 1000BASE-T descrambler acquisition error bit indicates that 1000BASE-T link establishment failed at the descrambler acquisition stage. The most likely expalantion for this failure is excessive pair skew.

Once this bit goes high it latches high until it is cleared by a subsequent successful 1000BASE-T descrambler acquisition.

BitFields.Name: DspCblLen
BitFields.Documentation:
This field allows the cable length estimate determined by the DSP engine to be observed. This estimate is computed during establishment of a 100BASE-TX or 1000BASE-T link.

The reported cable length is in meters with the value 8'd255 indicating indeterminate.

BitFields.Name: Pair0PolInv
BitFields.Documentation: The pair 0 polarity inverted bit indicates that the PHY has detected that the polarity of the signal that it is receiving on pair 0 is inverted. The PHY can detect this condition in the case of a 10BASE-T link when the Pair01Swap bit is set or in the case of a 1000BASE-T link.

BitFields.Name: Pair1PolInv
BitFields.Documentation: The pair 1 polarity inverted bit indicates that the PHY has detected that the polarity of the signal that it is receiving on pair 1 is inverted. The PHY can detect this condition in the case of a 10BASE-T link when the Pair01Swap bit is clear or in the case of a 1000BASE-T link.

BitFields.Name: Pair2PolInv
BitFields.Documentation: The pair 2 polarity inverted bit indicates that the PHY has detected that the polarity of the signal that it is receiving on pair 2 is inverted. The PHY can only detect this condition in the case of a 1000BASE-T link.

BitFields.Name: Pair3PolInv
BitFields.Documentation: The pair 3 polarity inverted bit indicates that the PHY has detected that the polarity of the signal that it is receiving on pair 3 is inverted. The PHY can only detect this condition in the case of a 1000BASE-T link.

BitFields.Name: Pair23Swap
BitFields.Documentation:
The pairs 2 and 3 swapped bit indicates that the PHY has detected that dimensions 2 and 3 are swapped.

This bit is asserted when the PHY determines that it is receiving on pair 2 the signal that is being transmitted by the link partner on pair 2 whereas this signal is expected to be received on pair 3.

BitFields.Name: LateColCnt23Sel
BitFields.Documentation: This bit indicates that late collision counters 2 and 3 are selected for read. See LateColCnt02 and LateColCnt13 for more information.

Registers.Name: MseA
Registers.Documentation:
This address allows the mean squared error at the slicer to be observed for logical dimension A. This value is updated at the end of each adaptation cycle

To calculate the associated signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) during idle apply the following formula to the value read:

  SNR A (dB) = 33.11 - 10 x log10(MseA)

An SNR value better than about 21dB is good enough for nearly error-free performance.

Registers.Name: FcFrmCntH
Registers.Documentation: This address allows bits 31:16 of a latched copy of the frame checker receive frame counter to be observed. This copy of the counter is latched when RxErrCnt is read. The rationale for this is to keep the number of CRC errors and the associated number of frames synchronized. The receive frame counter counts the total number of received frames.

BitFields.Name: FcUszCnt
BitFields.Documentation: This field allows a latched copy of the frame checker undersized frame counter to be observed. This copy of the counter is latched when RxErrCnt is read. The undersized frame counter counts the number of received frames whose size (excluding preamble and SFD) is less than 64 bytes.

BitFields.Name: FcOszCnt
BitFields.Documentation: This field allows a latched copy of the frame checker oversized frame counter to be observed. This copy of the counter is latched when RxErrCnt is read. The oversized frame counter counts the number of received frames whose length excluding preamble and SFD is greater than the number of bytes specified by FcMaxFrmSize.

BitFields.Name: FcOddCnt
BitFields.Documentation: This field allows a latched copy of the frame checker odd nybble  frame counter to be observed. This copy of the counter is latched when RxErrCnt is read. The odd nybble frame counter counts the number of frames with an odd number of nybbles and is applicable only to 10BASE-T and 100BASE-TX.

Registers.Name: FgEn
Registers.Documentation:
When set this register enables the built-in frame generator. However as the frame generator operates off the diagnostics clock it is also necessary to enable this clock. This may be done by setting the DigaClkEn bit in the direct access address map.

When FgEn is set the GMII/MII interface to the ASIC core is disabled.

BitFields.Name: FgEn
BitFields.Documentation:
When set this register enables the built-in frame generator. However as the frame generator operates off the diagnostics clock it is also necessary to enable this clock. This may be done by setting the DigaClkEn bit in the direct access address map.

When FgEn is set the GMII/MII interface to the ASIC core is disabled.

Registers.Name: FgCntrlRstrt
Registers.Documentation: This address provides access to the frame generator control and restart registers (FgCntrl and FgRstrt).

BitFields.Name: FgCntrl
BitFields.Documentation:
This register controls the frame generator in accordance with the following encoding:

  3'b000  Generate no frames after completion of any current frame
  3'b001  Generate frames with random payload
  3'b010  Generate frames with payload of 0x00 repeated
  3'b011  Generate frames with payload of 0xFF repeated
  3'b100  Generate frames with payloaf of 0x55 repeated
  3'b101  Generate frames with psyload of decrementing bytes

Also see FgNoHdr and FgNoFcs.

BitFields.Name: FgRstrt
BitFields.Documentation:
When set this register restarts the frame generator. This feature is intended to be used in the case where the frame generator is in burst mode and has finished generating a burst. Setting FgRstrt in this case will cause the frame generator to start a new burst.

Use of this register is not recommended during a burst or when the frame generator is operating in continuous mode as any current frame will be interrupted.

Registers.Name: FgContModeEn
Registers.Documentation:
When set this register puts the frame generator into continuous mode. In this mode the frame generator keeps generating frames indefinitely.

When this bit is clear the frame generator operates in burst mode. In this mode the frame generator generates a single burst of frames and then  stops. The number of frames in the burst is determined by the FgNfrmH and FgNfrmL registers.

BitFields.Name: FgContModeEn
BitFields.Documentation:
When set this register puts the frame generator into continuous mode. In this mode the frame generator keeps generating frames indefinitely.

When this bit is clear the frame generator operates in burst mode. In this mode the frame generator generates a single burst of frames and then  stops. The number of frames in the burst is determined by the FgNfrmH and FgNfrmL registers.

Registers.Name: FgIrqEn
Registers.Documentation: When set this register indicates that the frame generator should generate an interrupt when it has transmitted the programmed number of frames.

BitFields.Name: FgIrqEn
BitFields.Documentation: When set this register indicates that the frame generator should generate an interrupt when it has transmitted the programmed number of frames.

Registers.Name: FgNoFcsNoHdr
Registers.Documentation: This address provides access to frame generator controls to disable inclusion of FCS and header fields.

BitFields.Name: FgNoFcs
BitFields.Documentation: When set this register indicates that the frame generator should not add the FCS field at the end of the frame.

BitFields.Name: FgNoHdr
BitFields.Documentation:
When set this register indicates that the frame generator should not add the header fields - destination and source addresses and length/tag - at the start of the frame.

Note that 7 bytes of preamble and an SFD are always generated.

Registers.Name: FgFrmLen
Registers.Documentation:
This register specifies the length in bytes of the data field of the frames to be generated by the frame generator. The frame length itself may be determined by adding 18 to this value - 6 bytes each for the destination and source address fields, 2 bytes for the length field and 4 bytes for the FCS field.

Note that since the minimum Ethernet frame length is 64 bytes this value should not normally be reduced below 46. If a value lower than 46 is programmed then the frame generator will use the value specified and will not implement padding.

Note that since the minimum Ethernet frame length is 64 bytes this value should not normally be reduced below 46. If a value lower than 46 is programmed then the frame generator will use the value specified and will not implement padding.

Registers.Name: FgIfgLen

Registers.Name: FgNfrmH
Registers.Documentation:
This register specifies bits 31:16 of the number of frames to be generated in a single burst.

This value is only applicable when the frame generator is in burst mode.

Registers.Name: FgDone

Registers.Name: FgLpiEn
Registers.Documentation:
When set this register enables the generation of LPI requests by the frame generator.

When this register is set the frame generator asserts the LPI request each time it has finished generating FgLpiNfrm frames. Once the frame generator asserts the LPI request it keeps it asserted for a time determined by FgLpiN40nsm1H and FgLpiN40nsm1L. After deasserting the LPI request the frame generator waits for a time determined by FgLpiWakeN40nsm1 before starting to generate the next set of frames.

After deasserting the LPI request the frame generator waits for a time determined by FgLpiWakeN40nsm1 before starting to generate the next set of frames.

This register specifies bits 23:16 of the LPI request duration. Add 1 to the value specified by bits 23:0 and then multiply by 40 to get the duration in ns. By default the duration is set to 64ms.

The value specified here is replaced by a randomly generated value when FgLpiRndEnH is set.

Registers.Name: LnkWdEn
Registers.Documentation:
When set this register enables the link watchdog timer. If no activity is observed on the line consistent with the presence of a link partner that is seeking to establish a link then after a period of time determined by LnkWdN256ms the link watchdog timer will expire. 

When the link watchdog timer expires the PHY either enters the energy detect powerdown mode or restarts the link establishment process depending on the NrgPdEn register in the direct access address map.

Registers.Name: LnkWdInhEn
Registers.Documentation:
The PHY incorporates a link watchdog timer which normally expires after an extended period of link inactivity causing the PHY to either restart the link establishment process or to enter the energy detect powerdown mode.

Setting this register inhibits the link watchdog timer but only if  speed and duplex are forced, auto-crossover is disabled and energy detect powerdown is disabled. This allows  the break link delay that the PHY observes whenever the link establishment process is restarted to be avoided.

Registers.Name: B1000PwrThrLo
Registers.Documentation:
This register specifies the 1000BASE-T low ADC power threshold. The PGA controller attempts to adjust the PGA level to set the ADC power between the low and high threshold values.

Take the square root of the value specified by B1000PwrThrLo and multiply by 15.625 to get the minimum desired RMS value at the ADC in mV. Full scale at the ADC is 500mV.

A value of 8'd45 corresponds to 105mV RMS at the ADC.

Registers.Name: B1000RtrnEn
Registers.Documentation:
When set this register enables 1000BASE-T retrain.

Figure 40-15a of clause 40.4.6.1 of Std 802.3 requires a PHY which is operating in 1000BASE-T mode to retrain if it detects that its receiver status is not OK. Such a retrain prevents data from being transmitted or received for a long period but does not cause the LinkStatLat bit in the direct address map to latch low.

When B1000RtrnEn is clear 1000BASE-T retrain is disabled. In this case once the receiver status becomes not OK it will always result in the link dropping.

Registers.Name: SkipWaitCAck
Registers.Documentation:
When set this register causes the PHY to skip the wait that is normally allowed for the link partner to complete its final auto-negotiation acknowledgement.

When the PHY is operating in 1000BASE-T mode as master it implements a delay before attempting to train its receiver. This delay is to allow time for the 1000BASE-T slave to start transmitting. The delay is divided into two parts with the first part comprising a delay of  192ms for the link partner to complete acknowledgement. The SkipWaitCAck register allows this delay to be skipped and is primarily intended for use in simulation.

BitFields.Name: SkipWaitCAck
BitFields.Documentation:
When set this register causes the PHY to skip the wait that is normally allowed for the link partner to complete its final auto-negotiation acknowledgement.

When the PHY is operating in 1000BASE-T mode as master it implements a delay before attempting to train its receiver. This delay is to allow time for the 1000BASE-T slave to start transmitting. The delay is divided into two parts with the first part comprising a delay of  192ms for the link partner to complete acknowledgement. The SkipWaitCAck register allows this delay to be skipped and is primarily intended for use in simulation.

Registers.Name: SkipWaitSlv
Registers.Documentation:
When set this register causes the PHY to skip the wait that is normally allowed for the slave to train its receiver.

The second part of the delay described under SkipWaitCAck comprises a configurable delay to allow the slave to bring up its reveiver. The SkipWaitSlv register allows this delay to be skipped and is primarily intended for use in simulation.

Registers.Name: WaitSlvCfg
Registers.Documentation:
This register allows the station management to configure the delay allowed for the 1000BASE-T slave to train its receiver. The encoding is as follows:

  2'b00  325ms
  2'b01  350ms
  2'b10  375ms
  2'b11  400ms

See SkipWaitSlv for more information on this delay.

Registers.Name: LpiWakeErrThrEn
Registers.Documentation:
When set this register enables the wake error counter threshhold.

The PHY implements a counter which is incremented in the event of a wake error and decremented in the event of a clean wake. When this counter reaches a programmable threshhold the PHY either initiates a retrain in the case of 1000BASE-T or brings the link down in the case of 100BASE-TX.

If LpiWakeErrThrEn is clear then excessive wake errors are ignored.

Registers.Name: FreqOffsFrcEn
Registers.Documentation:
When set this register enables the forced frequency offset specified by FreqOffsFrcVal. FreqOffsFrcEn may be configured either to self clear after one cycle or not using FreqOffsFrcEnSc.

When a frequency offset is applied the PHY uses the phase mixer to synthesize a clock which has a different frequency from that of the free-running clock. The free-running clock is always locked to the reference clock frequency.

One useful application of this feature is where two PHYs are given the same reference clock frequency and configured to establish a 1000BASE-T link. Now if a frequency offset is forced on the master side then the slave must cope with a precisely controlled frequency offset.

BitFields.Name: FreqOffsFrcEn
BitFields.Documentation:
When set this register enables the forced frequency offset specified by FreqOffsFrcVal. FreqOffsFrcEn may be configured either to self clear after one cycle or not using FreqOffsFrcEnSc.

When a frequency offset is applied the PHY uses the phase mixer to synthesize a clock which has a different frequency from that of the free-running clock. The free-running clock is always locked to the reference clock frequency.

One useful application of this feature is where two PHYs are given the same reference clock frequency and configured to establish a 1000BASE-T link. Now if a frequency offset is forced on the master side then the slave must cope with a precisely controlled frequency offset.

Registers.Name: FreqOffsFrcEnSc
Registers.Documentation: When set this register causes FreqOffsFrcEn to self-clear after one cycle. This capability is useful when it is desired to implement a frequency hit when the PHY is configured for 1000BASE-T slave operation. If FreqOffsFrcEn is set when FreqOffsFrcEnSc is set then the frequency offset specified by FreqOffsFrcVal will be applied for one cycle only. This will cause the recovered clock frequency of the slave device to jump and it will then have to recover from this jump by itself.

BitFields.Name: FreqOffsFrcEnSc
BitFields.Documentation: When set this register causes FreqOffsFrcEn to self-clear after one cycle. This capability is useful when it is desired to implement a frequency hit when the PHY is configured for 1000BASE-T slave operation. If FreqOffsFrcEn is set when FreqOffsFrcEnSc is set then the frequency offset specified by FreqOffsFrcVal will be applied for one cycle only. This will cause the recovered clock frequency of the slave device to jump and it will then have to recover from this jump by itself.

Registers.Name: FreqOffsFrcVal
Registers.Documentation:
This register allows a forced frequency offset to be specified when FreqOffsFrcEn is set.

Multiply the associated 16-bit 2s complement integer by 2**(-25) to determine the frequency offset expressed as a fraction of the free-running clock frequency. For example a 100 PPM frequency offset may be programmed by writing the value 16'd3355.

BitFields.Name: FreqOffsFrcVal
BitFields.Documentation:
This register allows a forced frequency offset to be specified when FreqOffsFrcEn is set.

Multiply the associated 16-bit 2s complement integer by 2**(-25) to determine the frequency offset expressed as a fraction of the free-running clock frequency. For example a 100 PPM frequency offset may be programmed by writing the value 16'd3355.

Registers.Name: FreqOffsTrunc
Registers.Documentation:
This address allows the timing recovery frequency offset to be read. This capability is useful when the PHY is operating in 100BASE-TX or in 1000BASE-T as slave as it allows the frequency offset of the link partner to be determined with reference to the local free-running clock. Note that the PHY maintains a 34-bit frequency offset register of which only the uppermost 16 bits may be read.

Multiply the associated 16-bit 2s complement integer by 2**(-25) to determine the frequency offset expressed as a fraction of the free-running clock frequency.

Note that the PHY maintains a 34-bit frequency offset register of which only the uppermost 16 bits may be read.

Multiply the associated 16-bit 2s complement integer by 2**(-25) to determine the frequency offset expressed as a fraction of the free-running clock frequency.

Registers.Name: LnkPulThrAct
Registers.Documentation:
This register specifies the activity threshold to be used when detecting link pulses. These pulses may be 10BASE-T link integrity pulses or auto-negotiation fast link pulses. All such pulses must conform to the template requirements of Figure 14-12 in clause 14.3.1.2.2 of Std 802.3.

The link pulse detection scheme used by the PHY involves a number of digital filtering steps. The combined effect of the analog receive processing along with this digital filtering is to give a peak filter output 4.096 times the magnitude of the incoming pulse on the line.

The output from the link pulse filtering is checked against the template of Figure 14-12 using a number of simple checks.  The first check involves ensuring that the absolute value of the peak filter output exceeds the activity threshold specified here. The value of 13'd834 corresponds to a link pulse magnitude of 203.6mV on the line.

BitFields.Name: LnkPulThrAct
BitFields.Documentation:
This register specifies the activity threshold to be used when detecting link pulses. These pulses may be 10BASE-T link integrity pulses or auto-negotiation fast link pulses. All such pulses must conform to the template requirements of Figure 14-12 in clause 14.3.1.2.2 of Std 802.3.

The link pulse detection scheme used by the PHY involves a number of digital filtering steps. The combined effect of the analog receive processing along with this digital filtering is to give a peak filter output 4.096 times the magnitude of the incoming pulse on the line.

The output from the link pulse filtering is checked against the template of Figure 14-12 using a number of simple checks.  The first check involves ensuring that the absolute value of the peak filter output exceeds the activity threshold specified here. The value of 13'd834 corresponds to a link pulse magnitude of 203.6mV on the line.

Registers.Name: LnkPulThrInact
Registers.Documentation:
This register specifies the inactivity threshold to be used when detecting link pulses. See LnkPulThrAct for more information.

Once a signal has been detected which exceeds the activity threshold the PHY waits for a period of time specified by LnkPulDlyAct and then checks that the signal has dropped below the inactivity threshold specified here. The signal is then required to remain below the inactivity threshold for a period specified by LnkPulDlyInact.

The value of 13'd533 corresponds to  a magnitude of 130.1mV on the line.

If after exceeding the activity threshold the signal changes polarity and exceeds the activity threshold again then the PHY waits for a period of time specified by LnkPulDlyInvPolAct before checking that the signal is below the inactivity threshold.

Registers.Name: LnkPulDlyAct
Registers.Documentation:

Add 1 to the value specified and multiply by 0.08 to get the delay in BT.

Registers.Name: TclkFreeSel
Registers.Documentation: When set this register selects the free-running clock of the PHY as the test clock. Otherwise the recovered clock is selected. The free-running clock corresponds to the output of the PLL and is used as the transmit clock in 100BASE-TX mode. The recovered clock corresponds to the output of the phase selector and is used as the transmit clock in 1000BASE-T mode.

Registers.Name: CfgPtr
Registers.Documentation:
The optimum settings for several of the AFE control registers depend on the platform. In order to allow a platform specific initialization to be conveniently performed the PHY provides a means to configure these registers with the minimum number of MDIO write operations. This is achieved by providing a configuration table which contains default values for the relevant AFE control registers with the associated bits packed together.

The CfgPtr register provides an index into the configuration table. Accessing CfgData reads or writes the indexed table entry. CfgPtr is automatically incremented after each CfgData access except in the case of a write access where CfgPtrRst is set in which case CfgPtr is reset to 3'd0 after the access.

BitFields.Name: CfgPtr
BitFields.Documentation:
The optimum settings for several of the AFE control registers depend on the platform. In order to allow a platform specific initialization to be conveniently performed the PHY provides a means to configure these registers with the minimum number of MDIO write operations. This is achieved by providing a configuration table which contains default values for the relevant AFE control registers with the associated bits packed together.

The CfgPtr register provides an index into the configuration table. Accessing CfgData reads or writes the indexed table entry. CfgPtr is automatically incremented after each CfgData access except in the case of a write access where CfgPtrRst is set in which case CfgPtr is reset to 3'd0 after the access.

Registers.Name: CfgDataCtrl
Registers.Documentation:
This address provides access to PHY configuration table data (CfgData) and control (CfgRestartAneg and CfgPtrRst) registers.

Note that read and write accesses to this register address automatically increment CfgPtr (see details above).  Writing sub-field registers is usually done using read-modify-write operations, which involve two register accesses, meaning CfgPtr would be twice incremented.  Therefore, read-modify-write operations are not recommended for modifying sub-field registers here.

BitFields.Name: CfgData
BitFields.Documentation:
The CfgData field allows the PHY configuration table to be accessed. See CfgPtr for more information.

The association of the CfgData bits with the AFE control registers is shown in the configuration table bit map.

Note that when a register default is written via the configuration table the register itself is also immediately updated. However when a register is written directly the associated default value in the configuration table does not change.

Also note that the configuration table is only reset to its silicon default state in the event of a H/W reset. It maintains all user programmed settings in the event of a S/W reset.

BitFields.Name: CfgRestartAneg
BitFields.Documentation: If this bit is set when CfgData is written then auto-negotiation will be restarted. The rationale for this is that it is possible that modifying AFE control registers after linking has begun could affect the link partner.

BitFields.Name: CfgPtrRst
BitFields.Documentation: If this bit is set when CfgData is written then CfgPtr will be reset to 2'd0 after the write operation.

Registers.Name: B100TxDacSlew
Registers.Documentation:
This register allows the 100BASE-TX T/X DAC slew rate to be adjusted which provides a mechanism for tuning the T/X signal to fit a desired template.

This register works by selecting the clock I/P to the phase detector of a DLL. By choosing the clock I/P appropriately the DLL can be used to precisely tune a unit delay element. A series of such delay elements is then used to generate the intermediate clock phases for the T/X DAC.

As the optimum setting for this register is platform dependent its default value may be programmed via CfgData.

Registers.Name: B10TxResOffs
Registers.Documentation:
This register allows the 10BASE-T T/X termination resistance to be adjusted which provides a mechanism for tuning the termination seen looking in from the line.

As the optimum setting for this register is platform dependent its default value may be programmed via CfgData.

Registers.Name: B10TxTstMode
Registers.Documentation:
The PHY provides the ability to transmit a 10BASE-T test signal  consisting of either a 5MHz or a 10MHz square wave .

The B10TxTstMode register controls the 10BASE-T test signal in accordance with the following encoding:

  3'b000  10BASE-T test mode disabled
  3'b001  Transmit 10MHz square wave on dimension 0
  3'b010  Transmit 10MHz square wave on dimension 1
  3'b010  Transmit 5MHz square wave on dimension 0
  3'b011  Transmit 5MHz square wave on dimension 1

These test signals are intended to be used for making various measurements as specified in IEEE Std 1802.3d.

BitFields.Documentation:

  3'b010  Transmit 10MHz square wave on dimension 1
  3'b010  Transmit 5MHz square wave on dimension 0

Registers.Name: B100TxTstMode
Registers.Documentation:
The PHY provides the ability to transmit a 100BASE-TX test signal which cycles continuously through the valid MLT3 signal levels - zero, positive, zero, negative and so on. Each transmit level may be held for either 16ns (short dwell time) or 112ns (long dwell time).

The B100TxTstMode register controls the 100BASE-TX test signal in accordance with the following encoding:

  3'b000  100BASE-TX test mode disabled
  3'b001  Transmit short dwell time test signal on dimension 0
  3'b010  Transmit short dwell time test signal on dimension 1
  3'b011  Transmit long dwell time test signal on dimension 0
  3'b100  Transmit long dwell time test signal on dimension 1

The short dwell time test signal is intended to be used to measure duty cycle distortion as specified in clause 9.1.8 of ANSI Std X3.263.

The long dwell time test signal is intended to be used to measure waveform overshoot, amplitude symmetry and rise/fall times as specified in clauses 9.1.3, 9.1.4 and 9.1.6 of ANSI Std X3.263.

BitFields.Documentation:

  3'b100  Transmit long dwell time test signal on dimension 1

The short dwell time test signal is intended to be used to measure duty cycle distortion as specified in clause 9.1.8 of ANSI Std X3.263.

The long dwell time test signal is intended to be used to measure waveform overshoot, amplitude symmetry and rise/fall times as specified in clauses 9.1.3, 9.1.4 and 9.1.6 of ANSI Std X3.263.

Registers.Name: CdiagCntrl
Registers.Documentation: Cable Diagnostics Control Register

BitFields.Name: CdiagLenMtrs
BitFields.Documentation:
Cable length units.
0: centimeters
1: meters

BitFields.Name: CdiagActive
BitFields.Documentation: Read only bit to indicate that a cable diagnostics operation is in progress

BitFields.Name: CdiagBrkLnk
BitFields.Documentation: Break any existing link and restart auto-negotiation. This bit is self cleared.

BitFields.Name: CdiagXpairDis
BitFields.Documentation: Disable cross pair fault checking.

BitFields.Name: CdiagOnAneg
BitFields.Documentation: Run cable diagnostics every time auto-negotiation is run. This bit should only be set in the local PHY or the remote PHY but not in both. Running cable diagnostics from both ends of the cable can cause the operation to be aborted without a valid result.

BitFields.Name: CdiagRun
BitFields.Documentation: Run cable diagnostics immediately. This bit is self cleared when the cable diagnostics operation has completed. It is primarily intended for use while the PHY is in the standby state with LinkEn low.

Registers.Name: CdiagRslts
Registers.Documentation:
Cable Diagnostics Results Register

A 4-bit code is reported for each pair with the following encoding:

  4'd9  Pair busy. Link established or link partner in 100BASE-TX
            forced mode or 1000BASE-T test mode.
  4'd4  Cross pair short or Rt < 85ohms
  4'd3  Intra pair short or Rt < 85ohms
  4'd2  Pair open or Rt > 115ohms
  4'd1  Pair well terminated. No fault detected.
  4'd0  Invalid. Cable diagnostics did not complete successfully.

Unused codes are reserved.

BitFields.Name: CdiagRslt3
BitFields.Documentation: Result code for pair 3

BitFields.Name: CdiagRslt2
BitFields.Documentation: Result code for pair 2

BitFields.Name: CdiagRslt1
BitFields.Documentation: Result code for pair 1

BitFields.Name: CdiagRslt0
BitFields.Documentation: Result code for pair 0

Registers.Name: CdiagLen0
Registers.Documentation:
Length indication for pair 0.

Reports the estimated cable length in the case of a well terminated pair or the distance to the closest fault if any was detected. The length is given in centimeters by default but this can be changed to meters by setting CdiagLenMtrs. A value of 16'hFFFF indicates that the length could not be estimated due to a busy pair or if the cable diagnostics operation did not complete successfully.

BitFields.Name: CdiagLen0
BitFields.Documentation:
Length indication for pair 0.

Reports the estimated cable length in the case of a well terminated pair or the distance to the closest fault if any was detected. The length is given in centimeters by default but this can be changed to meters by setting CdiagLenMtrs. A value of 16'hFFFF indicates that the length could not be estimated due to a busy pair or if the cable diagnostics operation did not complete successfully.

Registers.Name: CdiagLen1
Registers.Documentation: Length indication for pair 1.

BitFields.Name: CdiagLen1

Registers.Name: NrgPdTxN512msm1
Registers.Documentation:
This register specifies the delay between transmit pulses when the PHY is operating in energy detect powerdown. See NrgPdTxEn in the direct access address map for more information.

Add 1 to the value specified and then multiply by 512 to get the approximate delay in ms. Note however that this delay will be randomly reduced by 0-15ms. This random element is intended to prevent lock-up.

Registers.Name: B100FldSlicerLvl
Registers.Documentation:
Slicer level for programmable slicer for 100BASE-TX fast link down function.
The slicer here is used to indicate that the slicer input is zero only, and so the absolute value of the slicer input is used.  The slicer level here is unsigned, and the bit weighting is [0:-4] (i.e. multiply the value by 0.0625 to yield the slicer level, which will be in the range [1.9375, 0.0]).
The default value specified a slicer level of 1.25.
